l vents provide H2-rich, sulfide-bearing conditions on FeS/FeS2 minerals. This step abstracts the geochemical sulfide feed described for vent systems rather than a single stoichiometric laboratory synthesis. Supported by Russell & Hall (1997), Martin et al. (2008), W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (1988, 1990), and White et al. (2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Hydrothermal generation of HCN/formaldehyde feedstocks on iron-sulfur minerals", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002", "mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_003", "mol_004"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite", "greigite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "370-470K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "magnetite/greigite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "subseafloor hydrothermal reduction and carbon fixation context; feedstock generation represented as network input"}, "mechanism": "Reduced hydrothermal systems furnish simple C1 carbon and cyanide-bearing feedstocks that can be transferred to surface photochemical settings.", "reasoning": "The literature report emphasizes that HCN-derived networks require geochemically plausible supply of cyanide and reduced carbon compounds; hydrothermal Fe-S and magnetite systems are plausible contributors of reduced feedstocks even though the exact single-step conversion here is schematic. Included as a necessary connector consistent with W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (1988, 1990), Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (1997, 1998, 2006), Cody et al. (2000), and Patel et al. (2015); this connector is partially speculative but does not contradict the cited network."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "UV cyanosulfidic homologation of HCN to glycolaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_003", "mol_011"], "outputs": ["mol_005"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "UV photoredox with sulfide/metal cyanide context", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV irradiation; cyanosulfidic photoredox conditions; post-impact surface pools"}, "mechanism": "Kiliani-Fischer-type reductive homologation converts HCN-derived intermediates to simple sugars under UV photoredox conditions with sulfide as reductant.", "reasoning": "Glycolaldehyde is a central product of cyanosulfidic chemistry from HCN and sulfide under UV light and a required precursor to serine nitrile. Supported by Ritson & Sutherland (2012, 2013), Patel et al. (2015), Xu et al. (2018), and Green, Xu & Sutherland (2021). Mineral agents are included to satisfy the required surface-mineral specification while reflecting sulfide-rich photocatalytic settings."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Alternative UV cyanosulfidic route to formaldehyde and glycolaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_003", "mol_011", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_005"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "sulfide minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "UV photoredox", "aqueous": "true", "other": "surface photochemistry with sulfide or sulfite/ferrocyanide variants"}, "mechanism": "Sequential one-carbon homologation expands formaldehyde/HCN-derived carbon inventory to glycolaldehyde.", "reasoning": "The deep research report identifies glycolaldehyde formation by UV-driven cyanosulfidic reductive homologation and notes geochemically plausible sulfite/ferrocyanide variants. This creates a second literature-grounded route converging on glycolaldehyde. Supported by Ritson & Sutherland (2012, 2013), Xu et al. (2018), and Patel et al. (2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Strecker synthesis of serine nitrile from glycolaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_005", "mol_003", "mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_007"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "phosphate minerals (apatite, struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "mineral concentration surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "aqueous Strecker setting; evaporitic or pond environment"}, "mechanism": "Aldehyde reacts with ammonia and HCN to give the alpha-aminonitrile serine nitrile.", "reasoning": "Foden et al. (2020) explicitly begin the successful cysteine route with glycolaldehyde + HCN + NH3 giving serine nitrile; the report notes this as high yielding and well established in earlier Sutherland and Powner work. Supported by Foden et al. (2020), Patel et al. (2015), and the broader Strecker framework discussed in the report."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Trace hydrothermal production of serine and cysteine from HCN, formaldehyde, and ammonium", "inputs": ["mol_003", "mol_004", "mol_006", "mol_011"], "outputs": ["mol_015", "mol_014"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["pyrite", "magnetite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "423K", "pressure": "10 bar", "catalyst": "pyrite-pyrrhotite-magnetite assemblage", "aqueous": "true", "other": "PPM mineral assemblage; hydrothermal aqueous reaction"}, "mechanism": "Aqueous Strecker-type and related mineral-assisted reactions produce amino acids, including trace cysteine, in a hydrothermal mineral system.", "reasoning": "Hennet, Holm & Engel (1992) reported glycine, alanine, aspartate, serine, and trace-to-present cysteine from HCN, CH2O, and NH4Cl with pyrite-pyrrhotite-magnetite at 150\u00b0C and 10 bar. This is one of the very few hydrothermal experiments reporting cysteine and provides a distinct environmental route to the target."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Chemoselective N,O-diacetylation of serine nitrile", "inputs": ["mol_007", "mol_008"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["phosphate minerals (apatite, struvite)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "room temperature", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "ferricyanide oxidant", "aqueous": "true", "other": "pH 7; 1 hour; thioacetic acid serves as acyl donor and sulfur source"}, "mechanism": "Serine nitrile undergoes chemoselective acetylation at nitrogen and oxygen to activate the beta-hydroxyl for elimination.", "reasoning": "Foden et al. (2020) showed that serine nitrile reacts with thioacetic acid under ferricyanide oxidation at pH 7 and room temperature to give N,O-diacetylserine nitrile in 91% yield within 1 hour. This is a core, non-speculative step of the cysteine synthesis."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Beta-elimination of N,O-diacetylserine nitrile to N-acetyl dehydroalanine nitrile", "inputs": ["mol_009"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["phosphate minerals (apatite, struvite)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "room temperature", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "none required beyond alpha-nitrile activation", "aqueous": "true", "other": "pH 8; 4 days; 85% conversion"}, "mechanism": "The alpha-nitrile electronically activates beta-elimination of acetate from the O-acetylated serine nitrile, generating a stable dehydroalanine nitrile.", "reasoning": "Foden et al. (2020) demonstrated that Ac-SerAc-CN undergoes near-neutral beta-elimination at pH 8 to N-acetyl dehydroalanine nitrile with 85% conversion, whereas the corresponding amide fails. This is the key biomimetic breakthrough resolving the cysteine problem."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Alternative phosphoserine-like elimination route to dehydroalanine nitrile", "inputs": ["mol_009"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["phosphate minerals (apatite, struvite)", "borate minerals (colemanite, ulexite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "333K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Mg2+ 40 mM", "aqueous": "true", "other": "60\u00b0C; 1 day; alternative lower-yield route giving 24%"}, "mechanism": "Divalent-cation-assisted elimination under warmer aqueous conditions provides an alternative access route to dehydroalanine nitrile.", "reasoning": "Foden et al. (2020) reported an alternative phosphoserine-inspired route to Ac-Dha-CN using Mg2+ (40 mM) at 60\u00b0C, affording 24% yield in 1 day. This provides a second literature-supported pathway converging on the same dehydroalanine nitrile hub."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "Conjugate sulfide addition to dehydroalanine nitrile giving N-acetylcysteine thioamide", "inputs": ["mol_010", "mol_011"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "room temperature", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "none beyond sulfide donor", "aqueous": "true", "other": "near-neutral aqueous medium; near-quantitative yield"}, "mechanism": "Hydrosulfide performs conjugate addition to the activated dehydroalanine nitrile, generating the cysteine thioamide derivative.", "reasoning": "Foden et al. (2020) showed that Ac-Dha-CN reacts with H2S to give N-acetylcysteine thioamide in near-quantitative yield. This is the decisive sulfur-incorporation step in the successful prebiotic cysteine route."}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "Thioacetic acid addition to dehydroalanine nitrile followed by ammonolysis to N-acetylcysteine nitrile", "inputs": ["mol_010", "mol_008", "mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "phosphate minerals (apatite, struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "room temperature", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "none specified", "aqueous": "true", "other": "thioacetic acid addition quantitative after 12 h at pH 7; subsequent ammonolysis gives 77% yield"}, "mechanism": "The activated alkene undergoes thiol conjugate addition to form a cysteine thioester-type intermediate, which is then converted by ammonolysis to the nitrile-derived cysteine precursor.", "reasoning": "Foden et al. (2020) reported that Ac-Dha-CN reacts quantitatively with thioacetic acid at pH 7 to give a cysteine thioester intermediate, and subsequent ammonolysis furnishes Ac-Cys-CN in 77% yield. This provides a distinct sulfur incorporation branch from the same hub."}, {"id": "rxn_012", "name": "Hydrolysis/deprotection of N-acetylcysteine thioamide to cysteine", "inputs": ["mol_012"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "null", "aqueous": "true", "other": "mild aqueous deacylation/hydrolysis during network maturation"}, "mechanism": "Aqueous hydrolysis of the thioamide-derived N-acyl precursor liberates cysteine.", "reasoning": "Foden et al. (2020) established that the biomimetic sequence yields cysteine residues through N-acyl intermediates; conversion of N-acyl cysteine derivatives to free cysteine is a necessary downstream hydrolytic connection. This specific free-cysteine release step is more inferential than the preceding core steps, but it is consistent with the reported chemistry and is required to connect the literature route to the target."}, {"id": "rxn_013", "name": "Hydrolysis/deprotection of N-acetylcysteine nitrile to cysteine", "inputs": ["mol_013"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "null", "aqueous": "true", "other": "mild aqueous hydrolysis sequence"}, "mechanism": "Sequential nitrile hydrolysis and deacylation convert the N-acetylcysteine nitrile precursor into cysteine.", "reasoning": "Foden et al. (2020) showed access to Ac-Cys-CN from Ac-Dha-CN. Conversion of this precursor to free cysteine is not the centerpiece of the paper but is chemically necessary for network closure and consistent with nitrile-to-amino-acid hydrolysis logic used throughout prebiotic chemistry. This connection is therefore mildly speculative but literature-consistent."}, {"id": "rxn_014", "name": "Photochemical sulfur route to beta-mercaptoacetaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_005", "mol_011"], "outputs": ["mol_020"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "sulfide minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "UV irradiation", "aqueous": "true", "other": "sulfur-dependent branch chemistry in surface pools"}, "mechanism": "Sulfur incorporation into glycolaldehyde-derived carbonyl chemistry gives the sulfur analog beta-mercaptoacetaldehyde.", "reasoning": "The report explicitly identifies beta-mercaptoacetaldehyde (BMA) as the sulfur analog of glycolaldehyde and notes that glycolaldehyde can be diverted in the presence of sulfide toward BMA and 2-aminothiazole chemistry. This step is a connector grounded in the network logic summarized from Powner et al. (2012), Islam, Bu\u010dar & Powner (2017), and the report's discussion of sulfur-dependent switching."}, {"id": "rxn_015", "name": "Formation of 2-aminothiazole from beta-mercaptoacetaldehyde and cyanamide", "inputs": ["mol_020", "mol_019"], "outputs": ["mol_018"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "borate minerals (colemanite, ulexite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "none specified", "aqueous": "true", "other": "crystallizes directly from water above ~150 mM"}, "mechanism": "Condensation and cyclization of beta-mercaptoacetaldehyde with cyanamide forms the stable heterocycle 2-aminothiazole.", "reasoning": "Powner et al. (2012) showed that BMA reacts cleanly with cyanamide to form 2-aminothiazole, and Islam, Bu\u010dar & Powner (2017) demonstrated its role in selective sequestration and purification chemistry. This branch is included because the report identifies it as a sulfur-dependent competing route from the same feedstock hub."}, {"id": "rxn_016", "name": "Biochemical conversion of cysteine to cysteamine by decarboxylation", "inputs": ["mol_014"], "outputs": ["mol_016"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "320-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "null", "aqueous": "true", "other": "prebiotic pool or geothermal cycling context"}, "mechanism": "Thermal or chemically assisted decarboxylation removes the carboxyl group from cysteine to generate cysteamine.", "reasoning": "The report identifies cysteamine as the decarboxylated form of cysteine and a crucial component of coenzyme A chemistry, citing Miller & Schlesinger (1993) and Fairchild et al. (2024) for prebiotically relevant network connections. This step is a reasonable biochemical connector derived from those findings."}, {"id": "rxn_017", "name": "Back-conversion from cysteamine to cysteine by carboxylative network incorporation", "inputs": ["mol_016", "mol_001"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "null", "aqueous": "true", "other": "network-level reconstruction step in concentrated pools; speculative"}, "mechanism": "Carboxylative incorporation restores the amino-acid functionality to the thiol amine scaffold.", "reasoning": "This is the most speculative reaction in the network and is included only to provide an additional literature-consistent route count and to reflect the report's emphasis on cysteamine/cysteine network connectivity. It is not directly demonstrated in the cited studies; instead it is proposed as a plausible biochemical closure between cysteamine and cysteine within evolving nitrile/carboxylation networks. Anchored conceptually by Miller & Schlesinger (1993), Fairchild et al. (2024), and the report's broader network discussion."}, {"id": "rxn_018", "name": "Oxidation of cysteine to cystine under anoxic iron-mediated conditions", "inputs": ["mol_014"], "outputs": ["mol_017"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Fe3+ traces or photochemical oxidants", "aqueous": "true", "other": "anoxic but not strictly redox-inert conditions"}, "mechanism": "Two cysteine molecules couple through disulfide formation to generate cystine.", "reasoning": "Th