raldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"UV photoredox with sulfide and cyanide\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Kiliani-Fischer-type reductive homologation under UV\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Sequential cyanide addition and photoreductive homologation extends glycolaldehyde to glyceraldehyde.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Glycolaldehyde and glyceraldehyde are linked in the cyanosulfidic protometabolism network and constitute a major convergence region connecting nucleotide and amino-acid precursor chemistry (Ritson & Sutherland, 2012; Patel et al., 2015; Green, Xu & Sutherland, 2021).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Strecker synthesis of serine nitrile from glycolaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_001\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_006\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mineral concentration and aldehyde stabilization\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Aqueous Strecker conditions in evaporitic pools; glycolaldehyde as aldehyde precursor\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Glycolaldehyde forms an imine with ammonia and then undergoes cyanide addition to yield the alpha-aminonitrile serine nitrile.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Foden et al. identify serine nitrile formation from glycolaldehyde, HCN, and NH3 as the correct prebiotic entry to cysteine chemistry; this route avoids the failed direct Strecker route to cysteine. Glycolaldehyde-derived serine nitrile is also embedded in earlier Sutherland/Powner chemistry (Foden et al., 2020; Patel et al., 2015).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Sulfur diversion of glycolaldehyde to beta-mercaptoacetaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"sulfur-rich photochemical pool chemistry\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Localized sulfide-rich surface setting; sulfur-dependent branch from glycolaldehyde chemistry\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Sulfur incorporation into glycolaldehyde-derived chemistry yields beta-mercaptoacetaldehyde as the sulfur analog relevant to aminothiazole formation.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The research report emphasizes that when sulfide is present, glycolaldehyde can instead lead toward beta-mercaptoacetaldehyde, diverting chemistry away from serine nitrile and toward 2-aminothiazole selection chemistry. This branch is included explicitly as a diversion, not as a productive direct cysteine route (Foden et al., 2020; Powner et al., 2012; Islam, Bucar & Powner, 2017).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"Formation of 2-aminothiazole from beta-mercaptoacetaldehyde and cyanamide\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_008\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"concentration/crystallization on mineral-rich pool margins\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Forms and crystallizes from water above approximately 150 mM\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Condensation and cyclization of beta-mercaptoacetaldehyde with cyanamide generates the thiazole heterocycle 2-aminothiazole.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is the literature-established fate of beta-mercaptoacetaldehyde under prebiotic conditions: it reacts cleanly with cyanamide to form 2-aminothiazole, which serves selection/purification roles rather than direct cysteine synthesis. This step is important because it explains why the sulfur aldehyde branch does not provide cysteine by Strecker chemistry (Powner et al., 2012; Islam, Bucar & Powner, 2017; Foden et al., 2020).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Chemoselective N,O-diacetylation of serine nitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_011\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"room temperature\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"ferricyanide oxidant with thioacetic acid in aqueous solution\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"pH 7; 1 hour; reported 91% yield\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Thioacetic acid transfers acetyl groups chemoselectively to the amino and hydroxyl groups of serine nitrile under mild aqueous conditions.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is the key Foden biomimetic activation step. Thioacetic acid acts as both sulfur source and acyl donor, and N,O-diacetylation of serine nitrile occurs at pH 7 and room temperature in 91% yield. Although ferricyanide is the experimental oxidant rather than a mineral, the required surface mineral field is specified here as a concentrating and phosphorylation-compatible geochemical context without altering the literature chemistry (Foden et al., 2020).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Beta-elimination of N,O-diacetylserine nitrile to N-acetyl-dehydroalanine nitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"room temperature\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"nitrile-enabled elimination\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"pH 8; 4 days; approximately 85% conversion; alternative phosphoserine/Mg2+ route omitted as separate node to avoid unsupported compression\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The alpha-nitrile electronically activates beta-elimination from the O-acetylated serine derivative, yielding the unusually stable dehydroalanine nitrile.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Foden et al. showed that the nitrile group is essential for near-neutral-pH elimination to dehydroalanine nitrile; the corresponding amide hydrolyzes instead. This is the decisive step that overcomes the historical instability problem of cysteine nitrile chemistry (Foden et al., 2020; Eschenmoser work as discussed in Foden et al., 2020).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Sulfide addition to N-acetyl-dehydroalanine nitrile to give N-acetylcysteine thioamide\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"room temperature\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"aqueous sulfide addition\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Near-neutral pH; near-quantitative yield\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Hydrosulfide performs conjugate addition to the activated dehydroalanine nitrile, furnishing the cysteine skeleton as a thioamide derivative.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This near-quantitative sulfur incorporation step is the principal solution to the cysteine problem in the literature. It converts the stable nitrile-activated dehydroalanine intermediate into a cysteine derivative under mild water-compatible conditions (Foden et al., 2020).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Thioacetic acid addition to N-acetyl-dehydroalanine nitrile to give cysteine thioester nitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_011\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"room temperature\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"thioacetic acid conjugate addition\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"pH 7; 12 hours; quantitative yield\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Thioacetic acid adds across the activated double bond of dehydroalanine nitrile to form a protected cysteine thioester nitrile.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Foden et al. reported quantitative formation of the cysteine thioester from Ac-Dha-CN and thioacetic acid, providing an alternative sulfur-entry route and a prebiotic acetyl-transfer competent intermediate (Foden et al., 2020).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Conversion of cysteine thioester nitrile to N-acetylcysteine nitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"room temperature\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"ammonolysis\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Reported 77% yield; neutral aqueous conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Ammonia converts the thioester-protected cysteine derivative into the corresponding N-acetylcysteine nitrile.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This step follows directly from the Foden route: the cysteine thioester intermediate undergoes ammonolysis to Ac-Cys-CN in 77% yield. It preserves the literature sequence without introducing unsupported alternate chemistry (Foden et al., 2020).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrolytic deprotection of cysteine nitrile/thioamide derivatives to cysteine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_016\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_017\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"aqueous hydrolysis/deacylation\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Mild anoxic pool or protocell conditions; step included as necessary network completion from Foden cysteine derivatives to free cysteine\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Aqueous hydrolysis and deacylation convert activated cysteine nitrile or thioamide derivatives into free cysteine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Foden et al. demonstrate prebiotic access to cysteine residues through stable N-acyl intermediates; explicit liberation of free cysteine is not the main focus of that paper, so this terminal hydrolytic step is included as a necessary connecting step to the requested target and is therefore somewhat more inferential than upstream steps. It is chemically consistent with the report's framing that the pathway solves prebiotic cysteine synthesis via cysteine derivatives and residues (Foden et al., 2020).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Trace hydrothermal synthesis of serine and cysteine in PPM mineral system\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_018\", \"mol_017\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"pyrite (FeS2)\", \"magnetite (Fe3O4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"150C\",\n        \"pressure\": \"10 bar\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"pyrite-pyrrhotite-magnetite mineral assemblage\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"HCN + CH2O + NH4Cl in aqueous mineral system; cysteine detected only at trace-to-present levels\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Complex aqueous Strecker-like and mineral-assisted reaction network generates multiple amino acids; serine is detectable and cysteine appears only in trace amounts.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is the only hydrothermal mineral experiment in the provided literature explicitly reporting cysteine detection. It must be treated as a trace, low-confidence side branch rather than a dominant route, consistent with the user feedback and the research report. The chemistry is not represented as a clean one-step mechanism but as an empirical hydrothermal network outcome (Hennet, Holm & Engel, 1992).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_013\",\n      \"name\": \"UV photochemical production of cysteine/cystine from reduced atmospheric mixtures\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_002\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_017\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"ambient\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"UV irradiation with H2S photosensitization\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"CH4/C2H6/NH3/H2O/H2S irradiation; low yield; cysteine and cystine detected with degradation during workup\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"UV-driven radical chemistry in reduced sulfur-bearing atmospheric or surface mixtures yields a low-abundance suite of amino acids including cysteine/cystine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Classical photolysis experiments by Khare and Sagan directly detected cysteine/cystine under UV irradiation of reduced mixtures containing H2S. This route is low-yield and not the main synthetic solution, but it is directly documented and therefore included as an independent surface pathway to the target (Khare & Sagan, 1971; Sagan & Khare, 1971).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_014\",\n      \"name\": \"Decarboxylation of cysteine to cysteamine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_017\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_021\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"thermal decarboxylation in concentrated prebiotic pools\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Included to represent network connection to coenzyme-like thiol chemistry\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Loss of carboxylate functionality from cysteine yields cysteamine, the thiol moiety relevant to pantetheine/coenzyme chemistry.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report identifies cysteamine as a key network connection downstream of cysteine and notes earlier demonstrations of prebiotic cysteamine synthesis, though not necessarily by this exact direct transformation in the cited report. This step is included as a downstream biochemical linkage and is more network-completion oriented than the core Foden route (Miller & Schlesinger, 1993; Fairchild et al., 2024 review context in report).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_015\",\n      \"name\": \"HCN oligomerization to adenine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_022\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"UV-assisted concentration and oligomerization\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Concentration-dependent HCN oligomerization in drying pools\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Pentamerization/oligomerization of HCN under prebiotic concentration regimes yields purine precursors including adenine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Included to keep the network connected to the broader cyanosulfidic/nucleotide context emphasized in the report, where cysteine synthesis is embedded in a network that also yields nucleotide precursors. This is background-consistent rather than central to cysteine synthesis (Patel et al., 2015; Green, Xu & Sutherland, 2021).\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Canonical cyanosulfidic-Powner sulfide route\",\n      \"description\": \"Main literature-supported route from HCN/H2S to glycolaldehyde, then serine nitrile, acetylation, dehydroalanine nitrile formation, sulfide addition, and hydrolysis to cysteine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Canonical cyanosulfidic-Powner thioacetic acid/ammonolysis route\",\n      \"description\": \"Main alternative sulfur-entry route in Foden et al. using thioacetic acid addition to dehydroalanine nitrile followed by ammonolysis and hydrolysis.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_016\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface pool entry from preformed glycolaldehyde to sulfide route\",\n      \"description\": \"Same Foden core route but entering the network at glycolaldehyde already accumulated in surface pools.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface pool entry from preformed glycolaldehyde to thioester route\",\n      \"description\": \"Preaccumulated glycolaldehyde feeds serine nitrile and the thioacetic-acid branch to cysteine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_016\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal sulfur supply feeding surface sulfide route\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal H2S feeds the surface cyanosulfidic and sulfur-addition stages, linking vent sulfur chemistry to the canonical Powner route.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_002\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal sulfur supply feeding thioacetic acid branch\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal sulfur availability supports the sulfur economy that enables the thioacetic-acid branch of the biomimetic pathway.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_002\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"Trace hydrothermal direct cysteine route\",\n      \"description\": \"Empirical minor cysteine production in hydrothermal pyrite-pyrrhotite-magnetite systems at 150C and 10 bar.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_018\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"Classical UV photochemical cysteine route\",\n      \"description\": \"Low-yield direct cysteine/cystine generation under UV photolysis of reduced sulfur-bearing atmospheric mixtures.\",\n      \"reaction_se