_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_003", "mol_004"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "UV photoredox with cyanide/sulfide chemistry on mineral surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV irradiation; cyanosulfidic network; evaporitic or subaerial pools; reductive homologation of HCN"}, "mechanism": "UV-driven photoredox reduction and homologation of HCN-derived intermediates generates simple carbonyl compounds including formaldehyde and glycolaldehyde.", "reasoning": "Surface cyanosulfidic chemistry is the literature-supported upstream feedstock source for glycolaldehyde, the key precursor to serine nitrile and ultimately cysteine. UV/H2S-driven homologation of HCN to glycolaldehyde is established in the Sutherland network (Ritson & Sutherland, 2012; Ritson & Sutherland, 2013; Patel et al., 2015; Xu et al., 2018; Green, Xu & Sutherland, 2021). Mineral specification here represents the required surface catalytic setting and sulfur-rich geochemical context described in the review."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Further cyanosulfidic homologation of glycolaldehyde to glyceraldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_004", "mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "UV photoredox with sulfide and cyanide", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Kiliani-Fischer-type reductive homologation under UV"}, "mechanism": "Sequential cyanide addition and photoreductive homologation extends glycolaldehyde to glyceraldehyde.", "reasoning": "Glycolaldehyde and glyceraldehyde are linked in the cyanosulfidic protometabolism network and constitute a major convergence region connecting nucleotide and amino-acid precursor chemistry (Ritson & Sutherland, 2012; Patel et al., 2015; Green, Xu & Sutherland, 2021)."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Strecker synthesis of serine nitrile from glycolaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_004", "mol_001", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_006"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "mineral concentration and aldehyde stabilization", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Aqueous Strecker conditions in evaporitic pools; glycolaldehyde as aldehyde precursor"}, "mechanism": "Glycolaldehyde forms an imine with ammonia and then undergoes cyanide addition to yield the alpha-aminonitrile serine nitrile.", "reasoning": "Foden et al. identify serine nitrile formation from glycolaldehyde, HCN, and NH3 as the correct prebiotic entry to cysteine chemistry; this route avoids the failed direct Strecker route to cysteine. Glycolaldehyde-derived serine nitrile is also embedded in earlier Sutherland/Powner chemistry (Foden et al., 2020; Patel et al., 2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Sulfur diversion of glycolaldehyde to beta-mercaptoacetaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_004", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_007"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "sulfur-rich photochemical pool chemistry", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Localized sulfide-rich surface setting; sulfur-dependent branch from glycolaldehyde chemistry"}, "mechanism": "Sulfur incorporation into glycolaldehyde-derived chemistry yields beta-mercaptoacetaldehyde as the sulfur analog relevant to aminothiazole formation.", "reasoning": "The research report emphasizes that when sulfide is present, glycolaldehyde can instead lead toward beta-mercaptoacetaldehyde, diverting chemistry away from serine nitrile and toward 2-aminothiazole selection chemistry. This branch is included explicitly as a diversion, not as a productive direct cysteine route (Foden et al., 2020; Powner et al., 2012; Islam, Bucar & Powner, 2017)."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Formation of 2-aminothiazole from beta-mercaptoacetaldehyde and cyanamide", "inputs": ["mol_007", "mol_008"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "concentration/crystallization on mineral-rich pool margins", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Forms and crystallizes from water above approximately 150 mM"}, "mechanism": "Condensation and cyclization of beta-mercaptoacetaldehyde with cyanamide generates the thiazole heterocycle 2-aminothiazole.", "reasoning": "This is the literature-established fate of beta-mercaptoacetaldehyde under prebiotic conditions: it reacts cleanly with cyanamide to form 2-aminothiazole, which serves selection/purification roles rather than direct cysteine synthesis. This step is important because it explains why the sulfur aldehyde branch does not provide cysteine by Strecker chemistry (Powner et al., 2012; Islam, Bucar & Powner, 2017; Foden et al., 2020)."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Chemoselective N,O-diacetylation of serine nitrile", "inputs": ["mol_006", "mol_011"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)", "phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "room temperature", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "ferricyanide oxidant with thioacetic acid in aqueous solution", "aqueous": "true", "other": "pH 7; 1 hour; reported 91% yield"}, "mechanism": "Thioacetic acid transfers acetyl groups chemoselectively to the amino and hydroxyl groups of serine nitrile under mild aqueous conditions.", "reasoning": "This is the key Foden biomimetic activation step. Thioacetic acid acts as both sulfur source and acyl donor, and N,O-diacetylation of serine nitrile occurs at pH 7 and room temperature in 91% yield. Although ferricyanide is the experimental oxidant rather than a mineral, the required surface mineral field is specified here as a concentrating and phosphorylation-compatible geochemical context without altering the literature chemistry (Foden et al., 2020)."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Beta-elimination of N,O-diacetylserine nitrile to N-acetyl-dehydroalanine nitrile", "inputs": ["mol_012"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "room temperature", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "nitrile-enabled elimination", "aqueous": "true", "other": "pH 8; 4 days; approximately 85% conversion; alternative phosphoserine/Mg2+ route omitted as separate node to avoid unsupported compression"}, "mechanism": "The alpha-nitrile electronically activates beta-elimination from the O-acetylated serine derivative, yielding the unusually stable dehydroalanine nitrile.", "reasoning": "Foden et al. showed that the nitrile group is essential for near-neutral-pH elimination to dehydroalanine nitrile; the corresponding amide hydrolyzes instead. This is the decisive step that overcomes the historical instability problem of cysteine nitrile chemistry (Foden et al., 2020; Eschenmoser work as discussed in Foden et al., 2020)."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Sulfide addition to N-acetyl-dehydroalanine nitrile to give N-acetylcysteine thioamide", "inputs": ["mol_013", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "room temperature", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "aqueous sulfide addition", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Near-neutral pH; near-quantitative yield"}, "mechanism": "Hydrosulfide performs conjugate addition to the activated dehydroalanine nitrile, furnishing the cysteine skeleton as a thioamide derivative.", "reasoning": "This n