k and the research report. The chemistry is not represented as a clean one-step mechanism but as an empirical hydrothermal network outcome (Hennet, Holm & Engel, 1992)."}, {"id": "rxn_013", "name": "UV photochemical production of cysteine/cystine from reduced atmospheric mixtures", "inputs": ["mol_002", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_017"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "ambient", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "UV irradiation with H2S photosensitization", "aqueous": "true", "other": "CH4/C2H6/NH3/H2O/H2S irradiation; low yield; cysteine and cystine detected with degradation during workup"}, "mechanism": "UV-driven radical chemistry in reduced sulfur-bearing atmospheric or surface mixtures yields a low-abundance suite of amino acids including cysteine/cystine.", "reasoning": "Classical photolysis experiments by Khare and Sagan directly detected cysteine/cystine under UV irradiation of reduced mixtures containing H2S. This route is low-yield and not the main synthetic solution, but it is directly documented and therefore included as an independent surface pathway to the target (Khare & Sagan, 1971; Sagan & Khare, 1971)."}, {"id": "rxn_014", "name": "Decarboxylation of cysteine to cysteamine", "inputs": ["mol_017"], "outputs": ["mol_021"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "thermal decarboxylation in concentrated prebiotic pools", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Included to represent network connection to coenzyme-like thiol chemistry"}, "mechanism": "Loss of carboxylate functionality from cysteine yields cysteamine, the thiol moiety relevant to pantetheine/coenzyme chemistry.", "reasoning": "The report identifies cysteamine as a key network connection downstream of cysteine and notes earlier demonstrations of prebiotic cysteamine synthesis, though not necessarily by this exact direct transformation in the cited report. This step is included as a downstream biochemical linkage and is more network-completion oriented than the core Foden route (Miller & Schlesinger, 1993; Fairchild et al., 2024 review context in report)."}, {"id": "rxn_015", "name": "HCN oligomerization to adenine", "inputs": ["mol_001"], "outputs": ["mol_022"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "UV-assisted concentration and oligomerization", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Concentration-dependent HCN oligomerization in drying pools"}, "mechanism": "Pentamerization/oligomerization of HCN under prebiotic concentration regimes yields purine precursors including adenine.", "reasoning": "Included to keep the network connected to the broader cyanosulfidic/nucleotide context emphasized in the report, where cysteine synthesis is embedded in a network that also yields nucleotide precursors. This is background-consistent rather than central to cysteine synthesis (Patel et al., 2015; Green, Xu & Sutherland, 2021)."}], "pathways": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "name": "Canonical cyanosulfidic-Powner sulfide route", "description": "Main literature-supported route from HCN/H2S to glycolaldehyde, then serine nitrile, acetylation, dehydroalanine nitrile formation, sulfide addition, and hydrolysis to cysteine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_003", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_011"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_004", "mol_006", "mol_013", "mol_014"]}, {"pathway_id": "P2", "name": "Canonical cyanosulfidic-Powner thioacetic acid/ammonolysis route", "description": "Main alternative sulfur-entry route in Foden et al. using thioacetic acid addition to dehydroalanine nitrile followed by ammonolysis and hydrolysis.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_003", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_009", "rxn_010", "rxn_011"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_004", "mol_006", "mol_013", 