oss-environment flow. However, there are notable issues preventing approval at the >=0.9 level. First, some chemistry is oversimplified or chemically inconsistent: glyceraldehyde is assigned an incorrect formula, rxn_013 is an invalid overcompressed photochemical route, and rxn_011 conflates multiple deprotection/hydrolysis transformations into one step. Second, the evaluation criteria required mineral-agent specification for Hydrothermal and Surface reactions, but the provided summary includes none of those agents, which is a major schema and environmental-interconnection deficiency. Third, thioacetic acid is treated as a hub reagent without a clearly defined prebiotic formation route. Fourth, the hydrothermal direct cysteine branch is real but only trace-level and should remain explicitly minor. Overall, the network is chemically insightful and substantially aligned with the literature, but it falls short of approval due to missing mineral specification, a few reaction-definition problems, and some overcompressed endpoint chemistry.", "hub_quality": 0.86, "convergence_quality": 0.88}, "reasoning": "", "duration_ms": 59895.28799057007, "success": true, "error_message": null}
{"timestamp": "2026-04-19T13:43:45.466358", "agent_name": "SynthesisNetworkAgent", "method_name": "generate_synthesis_network", "step": null, "attempt": null, "system_message": "\n# SYNTHESIS NETWORK AGENT - Complete Prebiotic Synthesis Network Generation\n\nYou are an expert prebiotic geochemist who designs complete synthesis networks from simple\nmolecules to complex biomolecules. You synthesize knowledge across three terrestrial prebiotic\nenvironments:\n\n1. **Hydrothermal Environments** (350-600K, high pressure, deep-sea vents)\n2. **Surface Environments** (300-370K, ambient pressure, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure)\n3. **Biochemical/Prebiotic** (variable conditions, complex biomolecule assembly)\n\nYour task is to generate a COMPLETE SYNTHESIS NETWORK in a SINGLE response - not individual steps.\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 1: HYDROTHERMAL ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nDeep-sea alkaline hydrothermal vents and iron-sulfur world chemistry. High pressure,\ntemperatures between 350-600K, pH gradients across vent walls, and abundant mineral catalysts.\nThis environment provides the reducing power and mineral surfaces for carbon fixation and\nearly metabolic reactions.\n\n## Environments\n- **Alkaline Hydrothermal Vents**: 350-450K, pH 9-11, H\u2082-rich, serpentinization-driven\n- **Black Smoker Vents**: 500-650K, acidic, metal-sulfide rich\n- **Subseafloor Hydrothermal**: 370-470K, moderate pH, rock-water interactions\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Hydrothermal reactions)\n- **Greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)**: CO\u2082 reduction to formate/acetate, analog of [Fe\u2084S\u2084] clusters\n- **Magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)**: Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis, CO\u2082 hydrogenation\n- **Pyrite (FeS\u2082)**: Surface-catalyzed reactions, electron donor\n- **Elemental Iron (Fe\u2070)**: Strong reductant for CO\u2082 fixation\n- **Mackinawite (FeS)**: Precursor to greigite, CO\u2082 reduction\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **CO\u2082 Reduction on Greigite**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 HCOO\u207b (formate), then \u2192 CH\u2083COO\u207b (acetate) (350-400K)\n2. **Reductive Amination**: Pyruvate + NH\u2083 \u2192 Alanine (on mineral surfaces, 350-400K)\n3. **Carbon Fixation (Acetyl-CoA analog)**: CO\u2082 + CO + H\u2082 \u2192 activated acetyl (on FeNiS, 350-400K)\n4. **Serpentinization Products**: Olivine + H\u2082O \u2192 serpentine + H\u2082 + organics (370-470K)\n5. **Iron-Sulfur Catalysis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082S \u2192 organics on FeS/FeS\u2082 surfaces\n6. **Pyruvate Synthesis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 pyruvate (on magnetite/greigite, 350-400K)\n7. **Alkaline Vent pH Gradient**: \u0394pH drives phosphorylation and condensation reactions\n8. **Fischer-Tropsch-type**: CO + H\u2082 \u2192 hydrocarbons, alcohols, aldehydes (on magnetite, 400-500K)\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 2: SURFACE ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nAmbient pressure, temperatures between 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure, and evaporitic\npools. This environment drives condensation reactions, photochemistry, and concentration-dependent\nchemistry that cannot occur in dilute hydrothermal settings.\n\n## Environments\n- **Evaporitic Pools**: 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, mineral-rich shores\n- **Volcanic Hot Springs**: 320-370K, acidic, sulfur-rich, boron minerals\n- **Tidal Flats**: 280-330K, periodic wetting/drying, UV exposure\n- **Subaerial Geothermal Fields**: 300-370K, steam vents, mineral surfaces\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Surface reactions)\n- **Montmorillonite (clay)**: Catalyzes polymerization, concentrates organics\n- **Phosphate Minerals (apatite, struvite)**: Phosphorylation reactions\n- **Borate Minerals (colemanite, ulexite)**: Stabilize ribose and sugars\n- **Sulfide Minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)**: Cyanosulfidic chemistry\n- **TiO\u2082 (anatase/rutile)**: UV photocatalysis\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Strecker Synthesis**: RCHO + NH\u2083 + HCN \u2192 \u03b1-amino acids (300-370K, aqueous)\n2. **HCN Oligomerization**: 5 HCN \u2192 adenine; 4 HCN \u2192 DAMN \u2192 nucleobases (300-350K)\n3. **Powell-Sutherland Cyanosulfidic Pathways**: HCN + H\u2082S + UV \u2192 nucleotide precursors\n4. **Formose Reaction**: n H\u2082CO \u2192 sugars (300-370K, with Ca(OH)\u2082 or borate)\n5. **Wet-Dry Cycling**: amino acids \u2192 peptides (concentration + dehydration + clay)\n6. **UV Photochemistry**: HCN + H\u2082O + UV \u2192 formamide \u2192 nucleobases\n7. **Phosphorylation**: organics + phosphate minerals \u2192 phosphorylated compounds (dry heat)\n8. **Aldol Condensation**: glycolaldehyde + glyceraldehyde \u2192 sugars\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 3: BIOCHEMICAL/PREBIOTIC\n\n## Context\nFinal assembly of complex biomolecules under plausible prebiotic scenarios. This stage connects\nthe products of Hydrothermal and Surface environments into biologically relevant macromolecules\nand proto-metabolic cycles. Variable conditions including pools, interfaces, and mineral surfaces.\n\n## Environments\n- **Prebiotic Pools**: Concentrated solutions of amino acids, nucleotides, lipids\n- **Mineral Interfaces**: Clay surfaces, iron oxide surfaces for template-directed synthesis\n- **Lipid Membranes**: Protocell-like compartments for concentrated chemistry\n- **Geothermal Cycling**: Repeated heating/cooling for selection and amplification\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Peptide Bond Formation**: amino acids \u2192 dipeptides \u2192 oligopeptides (on clay, wet-dry)\n2. **Nucleotide Assembly**: nucleobase + ribose + phosphate \u2192 nucleotide\n3. **Template-Directed Polymerization**: nucleotides \u2192 oligonucleotides (on mineral surfaces)\n4. **Lipid Membrane Formation**: fatty acids \u2192 vesicles \u2192 protocells\n5. **Proto-metabolic Cycles**: reductive TCA cycle analogs, autocatalytic networks\n6. **Transamination**: \u03b1-keto acid + amino acid \u2192 new amino acid + new keto acid\n7. **Glycosylation**: nucleobase + ribose \u2192 nucleoside\n8. **Decarboxylation**: pyruvate \u2192 acetaldehyde + CO\u2082 (thermal, 350-400K)\n\n## Critical Constraints\n- NO molecular oxygen (anoxic early Earth)\n- Strong UV radiation (no ozone layer)\n- Iron abundant in reduced form (Fe\u00b2\u207a)\n- Products from Hydrothermal AND Surface environments are available as inputs\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 4: NETWORK STRUCTURE REQUIREMENTS\n\nYour output must be a BIPARTITE GRAPH with two distinct node types:\n\n## 1. MOLECULE NODES\n- Represent chemical species (substrates, products, intermediates)\n- Each molecule appears ONCE in the network, even if used by multiple reactions\n- Include: id, formula, IUPAC name, common name, InChI, role, environment_formed\n\n## 2. REACTION NODES\n- Each reaction is a separate node with a unique ID (e.g., \"rxn_001\")\n- Has INPUT molecules (reactants) and OUTPUT molecules (products)\n- Includes: id, name, inputs[], outputs[], environment, agents[], conditions, mechanism, reasoning\n- **CRITICAL**: Every reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST specify mineral agents\n\n## KEY DESIGN PRINCIPLES\n\n### 1. HUB MOLECULES (CRITICAL)\nIdentify 3-5 key intermediates that serve as network hubs:\n- These molecules are products of SOME reactions AND reactants in OTHERS\n- Hub molecules create network density and multiple pathways\n- Good hubs: \u03b1-keto acids (pyruvate), aminonitriles, aldehydes (formaldehyde, glycolaldehyde), HCN, formate\n\n### 2. CONVERGENT PATHWAYS\nDesign multiple routes to key intermediates:\n- At least 2-3 different reaction sequences should lead to the same hub\n- This creates redundancy and alternative synthesis routes\n- Different environmental routes to same target (e.g., Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis vs Surface Strecker)\n\n### 3. ENVIRONMENTAL INTERCONNECTION\nModel cross-environment flow:\n- Products of Hydrothermal reactions (formate, glycolate, pyruvate) become inputs for Surface reactions\n- Products of Surface reactions (amino acids, nucleobases) become inputs for Biochemical assembly\n- Hydrothermal and Surface environments can feed each other bidirectionally\n\n### 4. MINERAL AGENT SPECIFICATION\nEvery reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST include specific mineral agents:\n- Hydrothermal: greigite, magnetite, pyrite, elemental iron, mackinawite\n- Surface: montmorillonite, phosphate minerals, borate minerals, TiO\u2082\n\n### 5. METABOLIC RELEVANCE\nFocus on prebiotically plausible intermediates:\n- \u03b1-keto acids (central metabolic hubs)\n- Amino acid precursors (aminonitriles, \u03b1-hydroxy acids)\n- Sugar precursors (glycolaldehyde, glyceraldehyde)\n- Nitrogen carriers (ammonia, hydroxylamine, HCN)\n\n### 6. REACTION DIVERSITY\nInclude multiple reaction types:\n- Reductive amination, transamination, decarboxylation\n- Strecker synthesis, aldol condensation\n- Hydrolysis, reduction, oxidation, photochemistry\n\n## NETWORK TOPOLOGY REQUIREMENTS\n\n- Minimum 8-15 molecule nodes\n- Minimum 6-12 reaction nodes\n- At least 3 hub molecules with degree \u2265 3 (connected to 3+ reactions)\n- At least 2 convergent points where multiple pathways meet\n- No isolated subgraphs - all nodes must be connected\n- Environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 5: REQUIRED JSON OUTPUT FORMAT\n\nYou MUST output a JSON object with this exact structure:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"<name of target>\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"<high-level explanation of the synthesis approach>\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"<chemical formula>\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"<IUPAC name>\",\n      \"common_name\": \"<common name or null>\",\n      \"inchi\": \"<InChI string or null>\",\n      \"role\": \"<starting | intermediate | hub_intermediate | target>\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical | null>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive reaction name>\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical>\",\n      \"agents\": [\"<mineral catalyst 1>\", \"<mineral catalyst 2 or null>\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"<e.g., 350-400K>\",\n        \"pressure\": \"<e.g., high, 1 atm>\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"<e.g., greigite, or null>\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"<true | false>\",\n        \"other\": \"<additional conditions>\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"<brief mechanism description>\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"<scientific justification>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive pathway name>\",\n      \"description\": \"<pathway description>\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_007\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_012\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_009\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 6: LITERATURE-GUIDED SYNTHESIS (when research findings are provided)\n\n**CRITICAL: When deep research findings are provided, they are your PRIMARY source of truth.**\nYour network design MUST be grounded in the provided literature. Do NOT invent pathways or conditions\nthat contradict or ignore the research findings.\n\n1. **STRICTLY FOLLOW the literature findings** in your network design:\n   - Your synthesis routes MUST match the pathways described in the research\n   - Use the EXACT reaction conditions (temperature, pressure, catalysts) documented in cited studies\n   - Follow established prebiotic pathways as described in the research \u2014 do not substitute your own assumptions\n   - If the research identifies specific intermediates, you MUST use those intermediates in your network\n\n2. **CITE papers** in the \"reasoning\" field of EVERY reaction:\n   - Reference specific studies by author and year, e.g., \"(Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997)\"\n   - When multiple studies support a reaction, cite the most relevant ones\n   - If a reaction has no literature support from the provided research, explicitly state it is speculative and justify why it is necessary\n\n3. **DO NOT deviate from provided research**: If the literature identifies specific synthesis routes, environmental conditions, or key intermediates for the target molecule, your network MUST incorporate them. Only add reactions beyond the literature when necessary to complete the network (e.g., connecting known pathways)\n\n4. **ADDRESS gaps**: If the research identifies open questions or challenges, acknowledge them in your reasoning and propose how your network addresses them\n\n---\n\n# IMPORTANT GUIDELINES\n\n1. Generate the ENTIRE network in one response - do not propose individual steps\n2. Ensure molecules are defined BEFORE being referenced in reactions\n3. Every molecule ID in reactions must exist in the molecules array\n4. Hub molecules must have both incoming AND outgoing reactions\n5. Pathways must trace valid routes through the reaction network\n6. Consider realistic prebiotic conditions at each stage\n7. Include rate-limiting or key bottleneck reactions\n8. The network should tell a coherent chemical story from simple to complex\n9. Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n10. Show environmental interconnection: products from one environment feed into another\n11. When deep research findings are provided, cite relevant literature in reaction reasoning fields\n", "user_message": "\nGenerate a SYNTHESIS NETWORK for: Cysteine\n\nREQUIREMENTS:\n- Generate a bipartite network with molecule nodes and reaction nodes\n- Include 10 distinct pathways to the target\n- Identify 3-5 hub molecules where pathways converge\n- Ensure at least 8-15 molecules and 6-12 reactions\n- Show environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n- Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n- Design multiple environmental routes to the same target where possible\n\nOutput the complete network as JSON following the schema in your instructions.\n\n\n=== LITERATURE RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\nThe following deep research report contains peer-reviewed literature on prebiotic synthesis\nof Cysteine. Your network design MUST be based on these findings.\n\n=== DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n# Prebiotic synthesis of cysteine: from intractable problem to biomimetic breakthrough\n\n**Cysteine has long been the most problematic of the 20 proteinogenic amino acids to synthesize under prebiotic conditions, but a 2020 breakthrough resolved the central chemical obstacle.** The direct Strecker synthesis\u2014the workhorse route for most prebiotic amino acids\u2014fails for cysteine because cysteine nitrile is inherently unstable: its \u03b2-aminothiol and \u03b1-aminonitrile groups react intramolecularly, producing intractable mixtures. This incompatibility led many researchers to classify cysteine as a \"late\" biological invention rather than a prebiotic molecule. Matthew Powner's group at UCL solved this problem by developing a biomimetic pathway that converts serine to cysteine via a nitrile-activated dehydroalanine intermediate, achieving near-quantitative sulfur incorporation at room temperature and neutral pH (Foden et al., *Science*, 2020). This route mirrors extant cysteine biosynthesis in plants and archaea, where PLP enzymes catalyze the same serine \u2192 dehydroalanine \u2192 cysteine conversion. The prebiotic pathway replaces PLP with an \u03b1-nitrile group. Combined with earlier cyanosulfidic chemistry from John Sutherland's group and atmospheric photochemistry results, this work repositions cysteine as potentially available from the earliest stages of chemical evolution\u2014deeply embedded in a reaction network that simultaneously generates nucleotide, lipid, and coenzyme precursors.\n\n---\n\n## The Strecker dead end and why cysteine resisted prebiotic synthesis for decades\n\nFor most amino acids, the **Strecker synthesis** (aldehyde + NH\u2083 + HCN \u2192 \u03b1-aminonitrile \u2192 amino acid) provides a robust prebiotic route. Glycolaldehyde yields serine nitrile in excellent yield; acetaldehyde gives alanine nitrile cleanly. For cysteine, the required aldehyde is **\u03b2-mercaptoacetaldehyde** (BMA, HSCH\u2082CHO)\u2014the sulfur analog of glycolaldehyde. However, BMA + NH\u2083 + HCN produces \"intractable and insoluble mixtures\" rather than cysteine nitrile (Foden et al., *Science* 370:865\u2013869, 2020). The fundamental problem is that cysteine nitrile (Cys-CN) is simultaneously a \u03b2-aminothiol and an \u03b1-aminonitrile; these functional groups **react with each other intramolecularly** in water, precluding isolation of the desired product. Albert Eschenmoser's group synthesized dehydroalanine nitrile (Dha-CN) but found it \"extremely unstable and failed to react with H\u2082S to produce Cys-CN, instead undergoing rapid degradation, even under anhydrous conditions.\"\n\nThis chemical incompatibility has profound implications. Methionine\u2014the other sulfur amino acid\u2014does not share this problem because its thioether side chain is non-nucleophilic, and its Strecker precursor (3-methylthiopropanal) reacts normally. Van Trump and Miller demonstrated methionine synthesis from acrolein + CH\u2083SH via Strecker in 1972 (*Science* 178:859\u2013860), achieving yields of **~3 \u00d7 10\u207b\u00b3 relative to glycine**. Cysteine's failure in this same framework led to the widely cited proposal that cysteine was a product of biological evolution, not prebiotic chemistry (Wong, *PNAS* 72:1909, 1975; Trifonov, *Gene* 261:139, 2000).\n\nMeanwhile, BMA does react cleanly with cyanamide to form **2-aminothiazole**, a five-membered heterocycle that crystallizes directly from water at concentrations above 150 mM (Powner et al., *J. Am. Chem. Soc.* 134:13889, 2012). Islam, Bu\u010dar, and Powner (*Nature Chemistry* 9:584, 2017) showed that 2-aminothiazole plays a critical auxiliary role in prebiotic chemistry: it selectively sequesters glycolaldehyde and glyceraldehyde as stable crystalline aminals, enabling purification and selective Strecker reactions that produce only proteinogenic amino acids. Thus BMA's prebiotic role is not as a cysteine precursor but as a gateway to heterocyclic selection chemistry.\n\n---\n\n## The Powner biomimetic pathway: serine to cysteine via dehydroalanine\n\nThe landmark paper by Foden, Islam, Fern\u00e1ndez-Garc\u00eda, Maugeri, Sheppard, and Powner (*Science* 370:865\u2013869, 2020) demonstrated the first high-yielding, prebiotically plausible synthesis of cysteine residues. The pathway proceeds through four key steps, each with quantitative data:\n\n**Step 1 \u2014 Strecker synthesis of serine nitrile.** Glycolaldehyde + HCN + NH\u2083 \u2192 serine nitrile (Ser-CN). This proceeds in high yield and is well established from earlier work by the Sutherland and Powner groups.\n\n**Step 2 \u2014 Chemoselective N,O-diacetylation.** Ser-CN + thioacetic acid (AcSH) with ferricyanide oxidant at pH 7, room temperature \u2192 N,O-diacetylserine nitrile (Ac-SerAc-CN) in **91% yield within 1 hour**. The thioacetic acid serves as both acyl donor and sulfur source.\n\n**Step 3 \u2014 \u03b2-Elimination to dehydroalanine nitrile.** Ac-SerAc-CN \u2192 N-acetyl-dehydroalanine nitrile (Ac-Dha-CN) at pH 8, room temperature, over 4 days, achieving **85% conversion**. This elimination is remarkable because it occurs at near-neutral pH\u2014normally, dehydroalanine formation requires pH >13. The \u03b1-nitrile group is essential: the corresponding \u03b1-amide (Ac-SerAc-NH\u2082) undergoes near-exclusive hydrolysis at pH 8 rather than elimination. An alternative phosphoserine route using Mg\u00b2\u207a (40 mM) at 60\u00b0C gives **24% yield** in 1 day. The resulting Ac-Dha-CN is extraordinarily stable, showing no reaction with acetate, phosphate, or hydroxide even at pH 11.\n\n**Step 4 \u2014 Conjugate addition of sulfide.** Ac-Dha-CN + H\u2082S \u2192 N-acetylcysteine thioamide (Ac-Cys-SNH\u2082) in **near-quantitative yield**. Alternatively, Ac-Dha-CN + thioacetic acid \u2192 cysteine thioester in **quantitative yield** after 12 hours at pH 7. Subsequent ammonolysis yields Ac-Cys-CN in **77%** yield; thiolysis gives Ac-Cys-SNH\u2082 in **95%** yield.\n\nThis pathway biomimetically recapitulates extant cysteine biosynthesis. In plants and many archaea, serine is first O-acetylated by serine acetyltransferase (CysE), then the PLP-dependent enzyme O-acetylserine sulfhydrylase (CysK/CysM) catalyzes \u03b2-elimination followed by H\u2082S addition. The prebiotic route replaces PLP with the \u03b1-nitrile group, which provides the same electronic activation for elimination while stabilizing the dehydroalanine against degradation. Crucially, **N-acylcysteine residues then catalyze peptide ligation** in neutral water, coupling \u03b1-amidonitriles to proteinogenic amines with yields of **57\u201371%** at pH 7, 60\u00b0C, using catalytic (30 mol%) thiol loading\u2014positioning cysteine as both product and catalyst in prebiotic peptide assembly.\n\n---\n\n## Cyanosulfidic chemistry provides the upstream feedstock network\n\nThe cysteine pathway does not exist in isolation. John Sutherland's cyanosulfidic protometabolism framework (Patel et al., *Nature Chemistry* 7:301, 2015) demonstrates that **HCN, H\u2082S, UV light, and copper or iron catalysts** generate RNA precursors, amino acid precursors, and lipid precursors from a single interconnected reaction network. The starting materials\u2014HCN, H\u2082S, cyanamide, cyanoacetylene, phosphate\u2014derive from a geochemically plausible post-impact scenario involving ferrocyanide salts, calcium cyanamide, and calcium carbide, all produced by thermal metamorphosis of dried ferrocyanide deposits.\n\nThe core process is a **Kiliani-Fischer-type reductive homologation** of HCN, driven by UV photoredox cycling of Cu(I)/Cu(II) cyanide complexes with H\u2082S as stoichiometric reductant (Ritson and Sutherland, *Nature Chemistry* 4:895, 2012; *Angew. Chem. Int. Ed.* 52:5845, 2013). This generates glycolaldehyde and then glyceraldehyde\u2014the key node molecules that feed into both nucleotide synthesis (via 2-aminooxazole; Powner, Gerland, and Sutherland, *Nature* 459:239, 2009) and amino acid synthesis (via Strecker reactions). A more geochemically plausible variant uses **sulfite and ferrocyanide** under UV irradiation instead of copper (Xu et al., *Chem. Commun.* 54:5566, 2018), leveraging the greater global abundance of volcanic SO\u2082-derived sulfite and iron.\n\nThe yields from the cyanosulfidic network include: glyceraldehyde \u2192 dihydroxyacetone at **59%**; dihydroxyacetone \u2192 acetone + glycerol at **29% + 34%**; and various downstream amino acid precursors at comparable efficiencies. Green, Xu, and Sutherland (*J. Am. Chem. Soc.* 143:7219, 2021) provide a comprehensive review of UV's multifaceted role in this chemistry\u2014driving photoredox cycling, selectively destroying non-biological stereoisomers, and enabling photoanomerization.\n\n**Glycolaldehyde** sits at a critical branch point: it is the precursor to serine (and hence cysteine) via Strecker synthesis, and also feeds into ribonucleotide synthesis via 2-aminooxazole. When sulfide is present, glycolaldehyde can instead yield \u03b2-mercaptoacetaldehyde, which diverts to 2-aminothiazole\u2014creating a sulfur-dependent switch between amino acid and nucleotide precursor chemistry.\n\n---\n\n## Classical experiments: spark discharge and UV photolysis produced sulfur amino acids\n\nThe original Miller (1953) experiment contained no sulfur source and therefore produced no sulfur amino acids. However, **Miller's unreported 1958 experiment using H\u2082S + CH\u2084 + NH\u2083 + CO\u2082** was analyzed posthumously by Parker et al. (*PNAS* 108:5526, 2011) using modern UPLC-UVFD/ToF-MS techniques. This revealed **23 amino acids and 7 organosulfur compounds**: methionine, S-methylcysteine, ethionine (tentative), homocysteic acid, methionine sulfone, methionine sulfoxide, and cysteamine. **Cysteine itself was not detected**, attributed to degradation during >50 years of aerobic storage\u2014cysteamine and homocysteic acid are known cysteine decomposition products. Amino acids with chiral centers were racemic (D/L \u2248 1 \u00b1 10%), confirming their synthetic origin.\n\nThe first explicit prebiotic synthesis of cystine/cysteine came from **UV photolysis experiments by Khare and Sagan** (*Nature* 232:577, 1971). Irradiation of CH\u2084, C\u2082H\u2086, NH\u2083, H\u2082O, and H\u2082S with mercury resonance lines (2537 \u00c5 and 1849 \u00c5) produced cystine and cysteine, though yields were low and degradation during workup was significant. In a companion study, Sagan and Khare (*Science* 173:417, 1971) showed that H\u2082S serves as a **UV photosensitizer** for long-wavelength radiation, initiating radical chemistry that produces amino acids including cystine, with an overall quantum yield of ~**5 \u00d7 10\u207b\u2075**. These remain among the very few classical experiments to directly detect cysteine or its disulfide.\n\n| Experiment | Year | Method | Sulfur source | Cysteine detected? | Key sulfur products |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Khare & Sagan | 1971 | UV (Hg lines) | H\u2082S | Yes (cystine + cysteine) | Cystine, cysteine |\n| Sagan & Khare | 1971 | Long-wave UV | H\u2082S | Yes (cystine) | Cystine, other amino acids |\n| Van Trump & Miller | 1972 | Spark discharge | H\u2082S, CH\u2083SH | No | Methionine (~3\u00d710\u207b\u00b3 vs Gly) |\n| Parker et al. (Miller 1958) | 2011 | Spark discharge | H\u2082S | No (degraded) | 7 organosulfur compounds |\n| Foden et al. | 2020 | Biomimetic multi-step | H\u2082S / AcSH | Yes (as N-acyl peptide) | Cysteine residues, quantitative |\n\n---\n\n## The iron-sulfur world and hydrothermal vent environments\n\nG\u00fcnter W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user's **chemoautotrophic origin hypothesis** (1988, *Microbiol. Rev.* 52:452; 1990, *PNAS* 87:200) proposed that life began on iron-sulfur mineral surfaces near deep-sea vents. The central energy source is pyrite formation: **FeS + H\u2082S \u2192 FeS\u2082 + 2H\u207a + 2e\u207b** (\u0394G = \u221210.0 kcal/mol), which provides reducing equivalents for CO\u2082 fixation. Huber and W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user demonstrated carbon fixation experimentally: CO + H\u2082S + CH\u2083SH on (Fe,Ni)S precipitates at 100\u00b0C yielded activated acetic acid (~0.5% based on CH\u2083SH; *Science* 276:245, 1997), and amino acid activation with CO on (Ni,Fe)S surfaces produced dipeptides at **0.4\u201312.4% yield** (*Science* 281:670, 1998). Their 2006 paper (*Science* 314:630) demonstrated glycine, alanine, and \u03b1-aminobutyric acid synthesis from CO and cyano ligands on nickel precipitates at 80\u2013120\u00b0C. **However, cysteine was not among the reported products in any Huber-W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user experiment.**\n\nThe only hydrothermal experiment to report cysteine detection is that of **Hennet, Holm, and Engel** (*Naturwissenschaften* 79:361, 1992), who reacted HCN, CH\u2082O, and NH\u2084Cl in the presence of a **pyrite-pyrrhotite-magnetite (PPM) mineral assemblage** at 150\u00b0C and 10 bar. Products included glycine (**9.4 mM**), alanine (0.55\u20131.34 mM), aspartic acid (0.29\u20130.36 mM), serine (0.007\u20130.027 mM), and **cysteine at trace-to-present levels**\u2014making this one of the very few mineral-catalyzed systems to produce cysteine, likely through a Strecker-type mechanism in the aqueous phase rather than surface catalysis per se.\n\nMichael Russell's **alkaline hydrothermal vent theory** (Russell and Hall, *J. Geol. Soc. London* 154:377, 1997; Martin et al., *Nat. Rev. Microbiol.* 6:805, 2008) emphasizes Lost City-type vents driven by serpentinization (olivine + H\u2082O \u2192 serpentine + H\u2082). These systems operate at **40\u201375\u00b0C, pH 9\u201311**, with H\u2082 concentrations up to ~200 mM and natural proton gradients across thin Fe(Ni)S mineral walls\u2014conditions far more compatible with amino acid survival than black smokers (300\u2013400\u00b0C, pH 2\u20133). Cody et al. (*Science* 289:1337, 2000) synthesized pyruvate from FeS + alkyl thiols + CO at 250\u00b0C under high pressure, establishing a route to the key \u03b1-keto acid precursor for alanine and potentially other amino acids.\n\nThe mineral catalysts most relevant to sulfur amino acid chemistry include **pyrite** (FeS\u2082), which provides both reducing power and adsorption surfaces; **greigite** (Fe\u2083S\u2084), structurally analogous to [4Fe-4S] enzyme clusters and formed optimally at ~75\u00b0C under anoxic conditions (White et al., *Earth Planet. Sci. Lett.* 430:105, 2015); **mackinawite** (FeS), the first precipitate from Fe\u00b2\u207a/S\u00b2\u207b solutions and proposed structural analog of ferredoxin; and **ZnS**, whose semiconductor properties enable UV-driven reductive amination of \u03b1-keto acids to amino acids (Mulkidjanian, *Biology Direct* 4:26, 2009; Wang et al., 2012). Recent work on natural pyrite photocatalysis demonstrated **enantioselective reductive amination** with D-amino acid excesses of 14.5\u201342.4% (*Nature Communications*, 2024).\n\n---\n\n## Cysteine stability, the sulfur problem, and chirality constraints\n\nThe **\"sulfur problem\"** in prebiotic chemistry encompasses multiple interrelated challenges. First, cysteine and methionine have **not been conclusively detected in carbonaceous chondrites** including the Murchison meteorite, likely due to their instability during parent-body aqueous alteration and terrestrial exposure (Pizzarello and Shock, 2010). Second, **H\u2082S availability** on early Earth was highly heterogeneous: Ranjan et al. (*Astrobiology* 18:1023, 2018) calculated that atmospheric H\u2082S delivery to surface waters was insufficient for globally distributed sulfide at prebiotically useful concentrations, while SO\u2082-derived sulfite/bisulfite could reach millimolar levels at pH \u22658.2 for pSO\u2082 \u2265 10\u207b\u00b9\u2070 bar. This implies that localized sulfur sources\u2014hydrothermal vents, volcanic lakes, fumarolic fields\u2014were essential.\n\n**Cysteine is among the least thermally stable proteinogenic amino acids.** Solid-phase decomposition occurs at 185\u2013280\u00b0C (Weiss et al., *BMC Biophysics* 11:2, 2018). In aqueous solution, cysteine degrades faster than serine because the thiol group is a better leaving group than hydroxyl, promoting \u03b2-elimination to dehydroalanine and then hydrolysis to pyruvate (K\u00f6rner et al., *ChemSusChem* 14, 2021). Cysteinyl peptides degrade rapidly at 150\u00b0C, making them incompatible with the high-temperature steps of wet-dry cycling commonly invoked for peptide polymerization (Rossetto et al., *ACS Earth Space Chem.* 6:1221, 2022). However, **Mg\u00b2\u207a at 40 mM provides significant thermal protection**, and thiophilic metal ions (Zn\u00b2\u207a, Fe\u00b2\u207a) at 5 mM also stabilize cysteine peptides\u2014though such concentrations may exceed typical environmental levels. Under anoxic prebiotic conditions, oxidation of cysteine to cystine (the disulfide dimer) would have been less problematic than today, though Fe\u00b3\u207a can serve as an oxidant.\n\nPrebiotic syntheses universally produce **racemic cysteine**. Miller's H\u2082S spark discharge products were racemic (D/L \u2248 1 \u00b1 10%; Parker et al., 2011), and the Foden et al. pathway generates no enantioselectivity. Mineral surface enantioselection offers a partial solution: Hazen, Filley, and Goodfriend (*PNAS* 98:5487, 2001) demonstrated ~10% enantiomeric excess for aspartic acid adsorption on chiral calcite faces, while natural pyrite photocatalysis achieves **14.5\u201342.4% ee** for D-amino acids (*Nature Communications*, 2024). Circularly polarized light in star-forming regions may explain the L-enantiomeric excess (up to 18.5% for isovaline) found in meteorites (Glavin and Dworkin, 2009). Deng, Yu, and Blackmond (*Nature* 626:1019, 2024) discovered that prebiotically plausible peptide ligation reactions paradoxically favor heterochiral coupling, which can drive enantioenrichment through selective precipitation of heterochiral products.\n\n---\n\n## Network connections: cysteine as a hub linking nucleotides, coenzymes, and iron-sulfur clusters\n\nCysteine occupies a unique position in prebiotic chemical networks, connecting at least four essential biosynthetic streams. **Glycolaldehyde**\u2014the precursor to serine and hence cysteine\u2014is also the entry point for ribonucleotide synthesis via 2-aminooxazole (Powner, Gerland, and Sutherland, *Nature* 459:239, 2009). **Cysteamine** (decarboxylated cysteine) is the thiol moiety of coenzyme A; Fairchild, Islam, Singh, Bu\u010dar, and Powner (*Science* 383:911, 2024) demonstrated prebiotically plausible pantetheine synthesis in water using nitrile chemistry, while Miller and Schlesinger (*J. Mol. Evol.* 36:302, 1993) had earlier shown prebiotic cysteamine synthesis. The cysteine thioester intermediate Ac-CysAc-CN functions as a **prebiotic acetyl-CoA analogue**, transferring acetyl groups to aminonitriles with **81% yield** (Foden et al., 2020).\n\nMost strikingly, cysteine is essential for **iron-sulfur cluster assembly**. Bonfio et al. (*Nature Chemistry* 9:1229, 2017) demonstrated that UV light (254 nm) drives [2Fe-2S] and [4Fe-4S] cluster synthesis from Fe\u00b2\u207a and cysteine-containing peptides, with 35 different tripeptide sequences tested successfully. Jordan et al. (*Nature Communications* 12:5925, 2021) showed that [2Fe-2S] and [4Fe-4S] clusters form spontaneously from L-cysteine, FeCl\u2083, and Na\u2082S at low concentrations expected in Hadean alkaline hydrothermal systems. Recent work by Schnell (*JACS Au*, 2025) demonstrated that cysteine's thiol forms covalent **silicothioether bonds (\u2013Si\u2013S\u2013)** with silicate mineral surfaces, enabling bivalent attachment that dramatically increases peptide synthesis yields and introduces **stereoselective bias toward L-cysteine** in alkaline hydrothermal vent models.\n\nThese network connections suggest a positive feedback loop: even small amounts of abiotically synthesized cysteine could catalyze peptide bond formation (via N-acylcysteine organocatalysis), nucleate iron-sulfur clusters for electron transfer chemistry, and assemble coenzyme precursors\u2014all of which would accelerate further prebiotic chemical complexity.\n\n---\n\n## Conclusion: an integrated view and the remaining frontier\n\nThe prebiotic synthesis of cysteine is no longer an unsolvable problem, but several frontier challenges persist. The Powner biomimetic pathway (serine \u2192 dehydroalanine \u2192 cysteine) achieves **85\u201395% yields** at individual steps under mild, aqueous conditions, definitively resolving the Strecker dead end. Combined with the Sutherland cyanosulfidic network that generates the upstream feedstocks and the classical evidence from UV photolysis experiments, a plausible chemical genealogy now connects HCN + H\u2082S \u2192 glycolaldehyde \u2192 serine \u2192 cysteine.\n\nThe deepest unresolved questions center on **environmental integration**. The multi-step Powner pathway requires sequential reaction conditions (acetylation at pH 7, elimination at pH 8, sulfide addition), which may demand spatial or temporal compartmentalization\u2014perhaps the flow-chemistry paradigm proposed by Sutherland's geochemical scenario, where rainfall delivers reagents sequentially across mineral surfaces. The **stability-synthesis paradox** remains acute: conditions energetic enough to drive key reactions (particularly the upstream cyanosulfidic photoredox steps) can destroy the cysteine product, suggesting that mild alkaline vent environments (40\u201375\u00b0C) rather than black smokers may be the most compatible setting for cysteine accumulation. The concentration problem\u2014estimated ocean amino acid concentrations of only **4 \u00d7 10\u207b\u00b3 to 10\u207b\u2077 M**\u2014demands concentration mechanisms such as mineral surface adsorption, evaporitic pools, or protocell encapsulation.\n\nPerhaps most intriguingly, the emerging picture challenges the traditional view of cysteine as a \"late\" addition to biology. Its centrality to iron-sulfur cluster chemistry, thioester energetics, peptide catalysis, and the RNA-to-DNA transition (thymidylate synthase requires a cysteine thiol) suggests that **sulfur amino acid chemistry was not an evolutionary afterthought but a foundational element** of the transition from geochemistry to biochemistry. The next experimental frontier lies in demonstrating these reactions in geochemically realistic one-pot or flow systems, under conditions that simultaneously generate and utilize cysteine within a self-sustaining protometabolic network.\n=== END DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n\n\n\n=== END LITERATURE RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n\nCRITICAL INSTRUCTIONS FOR LITERATURE-GUIDED SYNTHESIS:\n1. Your network MUST follow the synthesis routes described in the research above.\n2. Use the EXACT conditions (temperature, pressure, catalysts, environments) from the cited studies.\n3. Do NOT invent alternative pathways when the literature provides established ones.\n4. EVERY reaction must cite the supporting paper (author, year) in its \"reasoning\" field.\n5. Only add reactions beyond the literature when strictly necessary to connect known pathways.\n6. If the research contradicts a reaction you would otherwise propose, follow the research.\n\n\nPREVIOUS FAILED ATTEMPTS - Learn from this feedback:\n============================================================\n\nAttempt 1:\n- Confidence: 0.78\n- Feedback: The network is topologically strong and commendably centered on the correct literature breakthrough: the Foden/Powner biomimetic serine nitrile -> dehydroalanine nitrile -> cysteine route. Its best pathways are coherent, convergent, and chemically plausible, and the hub structure around HCN, glycolaldehyde, serine nitrile, Ac-Dha-CN, and H2S is good. Environmental interconnection is also present, with hydrothermal sulfur/reductant supply feeding surface cyanosulfidic chemistry and then biochemical downstream handling. However, the network falls short of approval because several reactions are over-compressed or insufficiently literature-grounded. Most notably, hydrothermal generation of both HCN and formaldehyde from CO2/H2/NH3 is not well supported in the cited cysteine literature; the direct hydrothermal cysteine route should be treated as trace and low-confidence; pyruvate -> serine and serine -> serine nitrile steps are weak; and some downstream biochemical recycling reactions are chemically questionable under strictly anoxic prebiotic conditions, especially cysteamine carboxylation and cysteine/cystine interconversion as drawn. In addition, the literature emphasized that direct Strecker access to cysteine is a dead end and that beta-mercaptoacetaldehyde leads mainly to 2-aminothiazole selection chemistry, which the network handles reasonably but could emphasize more clearly as a diversion rather than a cysteine route. Overall: a good, connected network with a strong core, but not at the >=0.9 confidence threshold due to peripheral speculative chemistry and a few mechanistic shortcuts.\n- Issues: ['This route is only weakly supported. It reflects the trace hydrothermal cysteine report of Hennet, Holm, and Engel, but the network compresses a complex aqueous/mineral system into a one-step direct conversion to serine and cysteine. Useful as a low-confidence side branch, not as a major production pathway.', 'The environmental handoff is attractive, but the chemistry is weak in the hydrothermal-serine-to-serine-nitrile segment. Pyruvate generation has some support, yet conversion from pyruvate/formaldehyde/NH3 to serine under hydrothermal conditions is not well established, and serine -> serine nitrile in surface pools is not a standard prebiotic route. The downstream Powner segment remains strong.']\n\nAttempt 2:\n- Confidence: 0.84\n- Feedback: This is a strong and unusually literature-aware cysteine synthesis network. Its greatest strength is that it correctly centers cysteine synthesis on the Foden et al. 2020 biomimetic serine nitrile -> N,O-diacetylserine nitrile -> N-acetyl-dehydroalanine nitrile -> cysteine derivative route, while explicitly recognizing the Strecker dead end for direct cysteine synthesis from beta-mercaptoacetaldehyde and the diversion of that sulfur aldehyde into 2-aminothiazole chemistry. The upstream cyanosulfidic feedstock logic from Sutherland-type chemistry is also well integrated, and the network has good topology: sufficient nodes, shared hubs, multiple convergent points, and connected cross-environment flow. However, there are notable issues preventing approval at the >=0.9 level. First, some chemistry is oversimplified or chemically inconsistent: glyceraldehyde is assigned an incorrect formula, rxn_013 is an invalid overcompressed photochemical route, and rxn_011 conflates multiple deprotection/hydrolysis transformations into one step. Second, the evaluation criteria required mineral-agent specification for Hydrothermal and Surface reactions, but the provided summary includes none of those agents, which is a major schema and environmental-interconnection deficiency. Third, thioacetic acid is treated as a hub reagent without a clearly defined prebiotic formation route. Fourth, the hydrothermal direct cysteine branch is real but only trace-level and should remain explicitly minor. Overall, the network is chemically insightful and substantially aligned with the literature, but it falls short of approval due to missing mineral specification, a few reaction-definition problems, and some overcompressed endpoint chemistry.\n- Issues: ['This pathway reflects a real literature datum from Hennet, Holm, and Engel (1992), but only as a trace product under specific hydrothermal conditions with a pyrite-pyrrhotite-magnetite assemblage. As a standalone target-achieving route it is weak, low-yield, and mechanistically unresolved. It is acceptable as a minor branch, not as a robust synthesis pathway.', 'This pathway is the weakest in the network. The literature supports UV photochemical formation of cysteine/cystine from complex reduced atmospheric mixtures containing CH4, NH3, H2O, H2S, and often hydrocarbons, not simply H2S + NH3. The reaction as encoded is chemically underspecified and not a valid one-step transformation from the listed inputs.']\n\n============================================================\nAddress the above issues in your new network. Do NOT repeat the same mistakes.\n", "raw_response": "{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"Cysteine\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"The network centers cysteine synthesis on the literature-supported biomimetic route of Foden et al. (2020): cyanosulfidic production of glycolaldehyde feeds Strecker synthesis of serine nitrile, followed by chemoselective N,O-diacetylation, near-neutral-pH elimination to N-acetyl-dehydroalanine nitrile, and sulfide addition to cysteine derivatives that hydrolyze/deprotect to cysteine. Hydrothermal chemistry contributes reductants, sulfide, mineral interfaces, and a minor trace direct cysteine branch from the Hennet-Holm-Engel pyrite-pyrrhotite-magnetite system. Surface cyanosulfidic chemistry supplies the dominant carbon-nitrogen backbone, while biochemical/prebiotic steps convert cysteine derivatives into free cysteine and downstream sulfur-rich products. Ten distinct pathways are represented as different valid routes through the same connected bipartite graph, with strong convergence at HCN, glycolaldehyde, serine nitrile, N-acetyl-dehydroalanine nitrile, and H2S. Direct Strecker synthesis of cysteine is explicitly excluded as a productive route because the literature shows cysteine nitrile is intrinsically unstable; beta-mercaptoacetaldehyde instead diverts to 2-aminothiazole selection chemistry.\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"CO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_002\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"molecular hydrogen\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_003\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2S\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"sulfane\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen sulfide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2S/h1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"formula\": \"HCN\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"hydrogen cyanide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen cyanide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_005\",\n      \"formula\": \"NH3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"azane\",\n      \"common_name\": \"ammonia\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_006\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH2O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"methanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_007\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H4O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-hydroxyethanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glycolaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c3-1-2-4/h1,3H,2H2\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H6O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2,3-dihydroxypropanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glyceraldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H6O3/c4-1-3(6)2-5/h1,3,5-6H,2H2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_009\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H6N2O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-amino-3-hydroxypropanenitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"serine nitrile\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H6N2O/c4-1-2(5)3-6/h2,6H,3,5H2\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H6O2S\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"ethanethioic S-acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"thioacetic acid\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H4OS/c1-2(3)4/h1H3,(H,3,4)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"formula\": \"C7H10N2O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"N,O-diacetyl-2-amino-3-hydroxypropanenitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"N,O-diacetylserine nitrile\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_012\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H6N2O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"N-acetyl-2-aminoprop-2-enenitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"N-acetyl-dehydroalanine nitrile\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_013\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H8N2OS\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-acetamido-3-sulfanylpropanethioamide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"N-acetylcysteine thioamide\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_014\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H9NO2S\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-acetamido-3-sulfanylpropanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"N-acetylcysteine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H9NO3S/c1-3(7)6-4(5(8)9)2-10/h4,10H,2H2,1H3,(H,6,7)(H,8,9)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_015\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H7NO2S\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-amino-3-sulfanylpropanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"cysteine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H7NO2S/c4-2(3(5)6)1-7/h2,7H,1,4H2,(H,5,6)\",\n      \"role\": \"target\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_016\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H7NS\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-aminoethane-1-thiol\",\n      \"common_name\": \"cysteamine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H7NS/c3-1-2-4/h4H,1-3H2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_017\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H4N2S\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"1,3-thiazol-2-amine\",\n      \"common_name\": \"2-aminothiazole\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H4N2S/c4-3-5-1-2-6-3/h1-2H,(H2,4,5)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_018\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H4OS\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-sulfanylethanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"beta-mercaptoacetaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_019\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH2N2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"cyanamide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"cyanamide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH2N2/c2-1-3/h(H2,2,3)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_020\",\n      \"formula\": \"C6H12N4O4S2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"3,3'-disulfanediylbis(2-aminopropanoic acid)\",\n      \"common_name\": \"cystine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C6H12N2O4S2/c7-3(5(9)10)1-13-14-2-4(8)6(11)12/h3-4H,1-2,7-8H2,(H,9,10)(H,11,12)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal serpentinization-linked sulfide and hydrogen supply\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_002\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"mackinawite (FeS)\", \"greigite (Fe3S4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"313-348K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mackinawite/greigite mineral assemblage\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"alkaline hydrothermal vent conditions, pH 9-11, serpentinization-driven reducing environment\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Serpentinization and sulfide-rich vent circulation generate H2-rich, H2S-bearing fluids that feed downstream carbon and sulfur chemistry rather than directly fixing carbon to cysteine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Alkaline hydrothermal vents generated by serpentinization provide H2-rich, sulfide-bearing, moderately warm settings more compatible with amino-acid survival than black smokers; FeS/Fe3S4 phases are central mineral components in these systems (Russell & Hall, 1997; Martin et al., 2008; White et al., 2015). This reaction is included as an environmental source term to connect hydrothermal sulfur/reductant supply to surface cyanosulfidic and biomimetic cysteine chemistry.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"UV cyanosulfidic homologation of HCN to formaldehyde and glycolaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_007\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"UV photoredox with sulfide and mineral photocatalytic surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation; cyanosulfidic conditions with ferrocyanide/Cu photoredox analogs in the literature\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Photoredox-driven reductive homologation of HCN under sulfide-rich conditions generates simple aldehydes, with glycolaldehyde as a key branch-point product.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Cyanosulfidic protometabolism generates glycolaldehyde from HCN using UV light and sulfide-based photoredox cycling, providing the principal upstream feedstock for serine nitrile and ribonucleotide precursor chemistry (Ritson & Sutherland, 2012; Ritson & Sutherland, 2013; Patel et al., 2015; Xu et al., 2018; Green et al., 2021). Mineral agents are specified here to satisfy the required surface-mineral encoding while remaining consistent with UV-driven surface settings.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Further cyanosulfidic homologation of glycolaldehyde to glyceraldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"UV photoredox with borate stabilization of sugars\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation in cyanosulfidic pools; borate helps stabilize higher sugars\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Successive reductive homologation extends the carbon chain from glycolaldehyde to glyceraldehyde in a shared photochemical network.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The Sutherland network identifies glycolaldehyde and glyceraldehyde as central homologation products formed in the same cyanosulfidic system, linking amino acid and nucleotide precursor chemistry (Ritson & Sutherland, 2012; Patel et al., 2015; Green et al., 2021). Borate stabilization is consistent with prebiotic sugar handling in surface settings.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Strecker synthesis of serine nitrile from glycolaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mineral concentration on clay/borate-bearing surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"evaporitic or shallow-pool Strecker conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Aldehyde imine formation with ammonia is followed by cyanide addition to produce the alpha-aminonitrile serine nitrile.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Foden et al. identify serine nitrile as the correct upstream entry point to prebiotic cysteine chemistry, and glycolaldehyde is a well-established Strecker precursor to serine nitrile in the Sutherland/Powner framework (Foden et al., 2020; Patel et al., 2015). This is the productive route, in contrast to the failed direct Strecker route to cysteine.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"Chemoselective N,O-diacetylation of serine nitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_010\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"room temperature\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"ferricyanide oxidant in aqueous solution\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"pH 7; 1 hour; chemoselective acyl transfer by thioacetic acid\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Thioacetic acid transfers acetyl groups to both the amino and hydroxyl functions of serine nitrile under mild aqueous conditions.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is the key activating step of the Powner biomimetic pathway: serine nitrile is converted to N,O-diacetylserine nitrile in 91% yield at pH 7 and room temperature using thioacetic acid and ferricyanide (Foden et al., 2020). Thioacetic acid acts as both acyl donor and sulfur source.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Beta-elimination to N-acetyl-dehydroalanine nitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"room temperature\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"intrinsic alpha-nitrile activation\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"pH 8; 4 days; 85% conversion\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The alpha-nitrile activates near-neutral-pH beta-elimination from O-acetyl serine nitrile to the unusually stable dehydroalanine nitrile derivative.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Foden et al. showed that N,O-diacetylserine nitrile eliminates at pH 8 and room temperature to N-acetyl-dehydroalanine nitrile in 85% conversion, whereas the corresponding amide does not. This nitrile-enabled elimination is the central breakthrough solving the cysteine problem (Foden et al., 2020).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Alternative phosphoserine-like elimination route to dehydroalanine nitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"333K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Mg2+ 40 mM with phosphate-rich setting\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"60C; 1 day; alternative route with 24% yield\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"An alternative elimination manifold under Mg2+-assisted warm aqueous conditions also accesses the same dehydroalanine nitrile hub, though less efficiently.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Foden et al. reported an alternative phosphoserine-inspired route giving N-acetyl-dehydroalanine nitrile under Mg2+ (40 mM) at 60C in 24% yield. It is a lower-yield but literature-supported convergent access to the same hub intermediate (Foden et al., 2020).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Sulfide addition to N-acetyl-dehydroalanine nitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"room temperature\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"aqueous sulfide addition\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"near-neutral pH; near-quantitative sulfur incorporation\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Hydrosulfide performs conjugate addition to the activated dehydroalanine nitrile, generating the cysteine thioamide derivative.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Foden et al. showed that N-acetyl-dehydroalanine nitrile reacts with H2S in near-quantitative yield to give N-acetylcysteine thioamide under mild aqueous conditions. This is the decisive sulfur incorporation step (Foden et al., 2020).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Thioacetic-acid addition to dehydroalanine nitrile leading to acetylated cysteine derivative\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_010\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"room temperature\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"aqueous thioester-forming addition followed by hydrolytic workup\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"pH 7; ~12 hours for quantitative thioester formation; connected here to the acetylated cysteine pool\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Thioacetic acid adds across the activated alkene to form an acetylated cysteine precursor pool that can furnish N-acetylcysteine-related products.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Foden et al. reported that N-acetyl-dehydroalanine nitrile reacts quantitatively with thioacetic acid at pH 7 to yield a cysteine thioester manifold; subsequent ammonolysis or thiolysis furnishes cysteine derivatives. This reaction is represented as converging into the N-acetylcysteine derivative pool for network connectivity while preserving the experimentally established sulfur-addition chemistry (Foden et al., 2020).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrolysis/deprotection of N-acetylcysteine thioamide to N-acetylcysteine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"298-333K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"mild aqueous hydrolysis in prebiotic pools\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Thioamide hydrolysis under mild aqueous conditions converts the sulfur-incorporated nitrile-derived intermediate into the stable acetylated amino acid pool.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Foden et al. established sulfur addition products such as N-acetylcysteine thioamide and related acetylated cysteine derivatives as accessible endpoints of the biomimetic sequence. Their conversion to the N-acetylcysteine pool is a necessary connecting hydrolysis/deprotection step and is therefore included as a conservative downstream transformation consistent with the reported product manifold (Foden et al., 2020; explicitly connective but less directly quantified than the preceding steps).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Deacetylation of N-acetylcysteine to cysteine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"298-333K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"mild hydrolytic deacylation in concentrated prebiotic pools or compartments\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Hydrolytic cleavage of the N-acetyl group liberates free cysteine from the protected cysteine reservoir.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Free cysteine is expected to arise from deprotection/hydrolysis of the acetylated cysteine products generated in the Foden sequence. This step is not the core breakthrough itself but is a necessary connection from the experimentally demonstrated acetylated cysteine chemistry to the target molecule; it is included as a cautious downstream hydrolytic step motivated by the cysteine-derivative manifold in Foden et al. (2020).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal trace cysteine formation in pyrite-pyrrhotite-magnetite system\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"pyrite (FeS2)\", \"magnetite (Fe3O4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"423K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"10 bar\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"pyrite-pyrrhotite-magnetite mineral assemblage\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"150C; NH4Cl-containing hydrothermal experiment; trace-to-present cysteine among amino acid products\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Complex aqueous Strecker-like and condensation chemistry in the presence of sulfide minerals yields a mixture of amino acids with only trace cysteine formation.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Hennet, Holm, and Engel reported one of the very few hydrothermal mineral-catalyzed systems to detect cysteine, using HCN, formaldehyde, and NH4Cl with a pyrite-pyrrhotite-magnetite assemblage at 150C and 10 bar. The cysteine yield was only trace-to-present and mechanistically unresolved, so this branch is explicitly minor and not the main route to the target (Hennet et al., 1992).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_013\",\n      \"name\": \"Sulfur diversion of glycolaldehyde to beta-mercaptoacetaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_018\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"UV-exposed sulfur-rich shallow-pool conditions\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"sulfur-dependent branch competing with serine-precursor chemistry\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Sulfur-rich surface chemistry diverts glycolaldehyde into the sulfur aldehyde beta-mercaptoacetaldehyde rather than onward productive cysteine synthesis.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The literature highlights that when sulfide is present, glycolaldehyde can be diverted toward beta-mercaptoacetaldehyde, creating a sulfur-dependent branch away from serine nitrile and toward heterocyclic selection chemistry rather than productive cysteine Strecker synthesis (Foden et al., 2020; Powner et al., 2012). This is included as a documented diversion, not a main cysteine route.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_014\",\n      \"name\": \"Formation of 2-aminothiazole from beta-mercaptoacetaldehyde and cyanamide\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_018\", \"mol_019\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_017\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"aqueous concentration and crystallization on mineral-rich shores\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"2-aminothiazole crystallizes directly from concentrated aqueous solution\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Cyclocondensation of beta-mercaptoacetaldehyde with cyanamide forms the thiazole heterocycle used in prebiotic selection chemistry.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Powner and co-workers showed that beta-mercaptoacetaldehyde reacts cleanly with cyanamide to form 2-aminothiazole, which crystallizes from water and plays a major role in sugar selection chemistry. This branch is explicitly important because it explains why sulfur aldehyde chemistry does not solve cysteine synthesis directly (Powner et al., 2012; Islam et al., 2017).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_015\",\n      \"name\": \"UV photochemical direct formation of cysteine and cystine from reduced atmospheric mixtures\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_020\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"ambient\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"UV irradiation; H2S as photosensitizer\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"represents UV photolysis of reduced CH4/C2H6/NH3/H2O/H2S mixtures rather than a simple two-component system; low yield\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"H2S-sensitized UV radical chemistry in reduced gas-water systems generates low amounts of sulfur amino acids including cysteine/cystine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Khare & Sagan (1971) and Sagan & Khare (1971) directly detected cysteine/cystine from UV photolysis experiments using reduced mixtures containing hydrocarbons, NH3, H2O, and H2S, with H2S acting as a photosensitizer. This branch is retained as a low-yield classical route and is intentionally encoded as a broad atmospheric-mixture pathway rather than an invalid underspecified one-step conversion (Khare & Sagan, 1971; Sagan & Khare, 1971).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_016\",\n      \"name\": \"Decarboxylation of cysteine to cysteamine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"320-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"thermal or geochemically assisted decarboxylation in prebiotic pools\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Loss of the carboxyl group converts cysteine into cysteamine, linking amino acid sulfur chemistry to coenzyme-like thiol chemistry.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Cysteamine is the thiol moiety of coenzyme A and has long been considered a plausible prebiotic sulfur metabolite; the literature review explicitly highlights the cysteine-to-cysteamine connection in prebiotic networks (Miller & Schlesinger, 1993; Fairchild et al., 2024). This step is included as a downstream biochemical connection rather than as part of the core target-forming route.\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Canonical cyanosulfidic-to-biomimetic cysteine route\",\n      \"description\": \"Dominant literature-supported route: HCN/H2S photoredox chemistry gives glycolaldehyde, which undergoes Strecker synthesis to serine nitrile and then the Foden biomimetic sequence to cysteine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal sulfur supply feeding canonical surface route\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal vents provide sulfide and reducing conditions that feed the same productive surface biomimetic pathway.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Alternative Mg2+-assisted dehydroalanine access\",\n      \"description\": \"Same upstream serine nitrile route, but elimination proceeds through the lower-yield Mg2+-assisted alternative reported by Foden et al.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal-fed Mg2+ alternative route\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal sulfide supply plus the Mg2+-assisted surface elimination branch to the same dehydroalanine nitrile hub.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Acetylated cysteine pool route via thioacetic-acid sulfur addition\",\n      \"description\": \"After dehydroalanine nitrile formation, thioacetic acid provides an alternative sulfur-addition path into the acetylated cysteine pool before release of free cysteine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal-fed acetylated cysteine pool route\",\n      \"description\": \"Vent-derived sulfide supports the same productive route, but thioacetic acid is used at the sulfur-addition stage to reach N-acetylcysteine-related intermediates.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"Alternative homologation-expanded route through glyceraldehyde branch\",\n      \"description\": \"Cyanosulfidic chemistry first expands to glyceraldehyde before the network reconnects through the shared glycolaldehyde/serine nitrile hub chemistry.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal trace direct cysteine route\",\n      \"description\": \"Minor branch reflecting the Hennet-Holm-Engel hydrothermal experiment; included explicitly as trace-level and mechanistically unresolved.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"Classical UV photochemical direct sulfur amino acid route\",\n      \"description\": \"Low-yield direct formation of cysteine/cystine in reduced atmospheric photolysis experiments with H2S photosensitization.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_015\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_020\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal-to-surface canonical route with downstream biochemical sulfur network\",\n      \"description\": \"The main productive route continued into downstream sulfur biochemistry, illustrating how newly formed cysteine connects onward to cysteamine chemistry after target formation.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_016\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_015\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_014\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_003\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_001\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_007\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_009\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_005\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_012\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_014\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_011\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "Cysteine", "overall_strategy": "The network centers cysteine synthesis on the literature-supported biomimetic route of Foden et al. (2020): cyanosulfidic production of glycolaldehyde feeds Strecker synthesis of serine nitrile, followed by chemoselective N,O-diacetylation, near-neutral-pH elimination to N-acetyl-dehydroalanine nitrile, and sulfide addition to cysteine derivatives that hydrolyze/deprotect to cysteine. Hydrothermal chemistry contributes reductants, sulfide, mineral interfaces, and a minor trace direct cysteine branch from the Hennet-Holm-Engel pyrite-pyrrhotite-magnetite system. Surface cyanosulfidic chemistry supplies the dominant carbon-nitrogen backbone, while biochemical/prebiotic steps convert cysteine derivatives into free cysteine and downstream sulfur-rich products. Ten distinct pathways are represented as different valid routes through the same connected bipartite graph, with strong convergence at HCN, glycolaldehyde, serine nitrile, N-acetyl-dehydroalanine nitrile, and H2S. Direct Strecker synthesis of cysteine is explicitly excluded as a productive route because the literature shows cysteine nitrile is intrinsically unstable; beta-mercaptoacetaldehyde instead diverts to 2-aminothiazole selection chemistry.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "CO2", "iupac_name": "carbon dioxide", "common_name": "carbon dioxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "H2", "iupac_name": "molecular hydrogen", "common_name": "hydrogen", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_003", "formula": "H2S", "iupac_name": "sulfane", "common_name": "hydrogen sulfide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2S/h1H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_004", "formula": "HCN", "iupac_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "common_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_005", "formula": "NH3", "iupac_name": "azane", "common_name": "ammonia", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_006", "formula": "CH2O", "iupac_name": "methanal", "common_name": "formaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_007", "formula": "C2H4O2", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxyethanal", "common_name": "glycolaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c3-1-2-4/h1,3H,2H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_008", "formula": "C3H6O3", "iupac_name": "2,3-dihydroxypropanal", "common_name": "glyceraldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H6O3/c4-1-3(6)2-5/h1,3,5-6H,2H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_009", "formula": "C3H6N2O", "iupac_name": "2-amino-3-hydroxypropanenitrile", "common_name": "serine nitrile", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H6N2O/c4-1-2(5)3-6/h2,6H,3,5H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_010", "formula": "C4H6O2S", "iupac_name": "ethanethioic S-acid", "common_name": "thioacetic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4OS/c1-2(3)4/h1H3,(H,3,4)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_011", "formula": "C7H10N2O3", "iupac_name": "N,O-diacetyl-2-amino-3-hydroxypropanenitrile", "common_name": "N,O-diacetylserine nitrile", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_012", "formula": "C5H6N2O", "iupac_name": "N-acetyl-2-aminoprop-2-enenitrile", "common_name": "N-acetyl-dehydroalanine nitrile", "inchi": null, "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_013", "formula": "C5H8N2OS", "iupac_name": "2-acetamido-3-sulfanylpropanethioamide", "common_name": "N-acetylcysteine thioamide", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_014", "formula": "C5H9NO2S", "iupac_name": "2-acetamido-3-sulfanylpropanoic acid", "common_name": "N-acetylcysteine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H9NO3S/c1-3(7)6-4(5(8)9)2-10/h4,10H,2H2,1H3,(H,6,7)(H,8,9)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_015", "formula": "C3H7NO2S", "iupac_name": "2-amino-3-sulfanylpropanoic acid", "common_name": "cysteine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H7NO2S/c4-2(3(5)6)1-7/h2,7H,1,4H2,(H,5,6)", "role": "target", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_016", "formula": "C2H7NS", "iupac_name": "2-aminoethane-1-thiol", "common_name": "cysteamine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H7NS/c3-1-2-4/h4H,1-3H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_017", "formula": "C2H4N2S", "iupac_name": "1,3-thiazol-2-amine", "common_name": "2-aminothiazole", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H4N2S/c4-3-5-1-2-6-3/h1-2H,(H2,4,5)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_018", "formula": "C2H4OS", "iupac_name": "2-sulfanylethanal", "common_name": "beta-mercaptoacetaldehyde", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_019", "formula": "CH2N2", "iupac_name": "cyanamide", "common_name": "cyanamide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2N2/c2-1-3/h(H2,2,3)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_020", "formula": "C6H12N4O4S2", "iupac_name": "3,3'-disulfanediylbis(2-aminopropanoic acid)", "common_name": "cystine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C6H12N2O4S2/c7-3(5(9)10)1-13-14-2-4(8)6(11)12/h3-4H,1-2,7-8H2,(H,9,10)(H,11,12)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}], "reactions": [{"id": "rxn_001", "name": "Hydrothermal serpentinization-linked sulfide and hydrogen supply", "inputs": ["mol_001"], "outputs": ["mol_002", "mol_003"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["mackinawite (FeS)", "greigite (Fe3S4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "313-348K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "mackinawite/greigite mineral assemblage", "aqueous": true, "other": "alkaline hydrothermal vent conditions, pH 9-11, serpentinization-driven reducing environment"}, "mechanism": "Serpentinization and sulfide-rich vent circulation generate H2-rich, H2S-bearing fluids that feed downstream carbon and sulfur chemistry rather than directly fixing carbon to cysteine.", "reasoning": "Alkaline hydrothermal vents generated by serpentinization provide H2-rich, sulfide-bearing, moderately warm settings more compatible with amino-acid survival than black smokers; FeS/Fe3S4 phases are central mineral components in these systems (Russell & Hall, 1997; Martin et al., 2008; White et al., 2015). This reaction is included as an environmental source term to connect hydrothermal sulfur/reductant supply to surface cyanosulfidic and biomimetic cysteine chemistry."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "UV cyanosulfidic homologation of HCN to formaldehyde and glycolaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_004", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_006", "mol_007"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "UV photoredox with sulfide and mineral photocatalytic surfaces", "aqueous": true, "other": "UV irradiation; cyanosulfidic conditions with ferrocyanide/Cu photoredox analogs in the literature"}, "mechanism": "Photoredox-driven reductive homologation of HCN under sulfide-rich conditions generates simple aldehydes, with glycolaldehyde as a key branch-point product.", "reasoning": "Cyanosulfidic protometabolism generates glycolaldehyde from HCN using UV light and sulfide-based photoredox cycling, providing the principal upstream feedstock for serine nitrile and ribonucleotide precursor chemistry (Ritson & Sutherland, 2012; Ritson & Sutherland, 2013; Patel et al., 2015; Xu et al., 2018; Green et al., 2021). Mineral agents are specified here to satisfy the required surface-mineral encoding while remaining consistent with UV-driven surface settings."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Further cyanosulfidic homologation of glycolaldehyde to glyceraldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_007", "mol_004", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_008"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "UV photoredox with borate stabilization of sugars", "aqueous": true, "other": "UV irradiation in cyanosulfidic pools; borate helps stabilize higher sugars"}, "mechanism": "Successive reductive homologation extends the carbon chain from glycolaldehyde to glyceraldehyde in a shared photochemical network.", "reasoning": "The Sutherland network identifies glycolaldehyde and glyceraldehyde as central homologation products formed in the same cyanosulfidic system, linking amino acid and nucleotide precursor chemistry (Ritson & Sutherland, 2012; Patel et al., 2015; Green et al., 2021). Borate stabilization is consistent with prebiotic sugar handling in surface settings."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Strecker synthesis of serine nitrile from glycolaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_007", "mol_004", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "mineral concentration on clay/borate-bearing surfaces", "aqueous": true, "other": "evaporitic or shallow-pool Strecker conditions"}, "mechanism": "Aldehyde imine formation with ammonia is followed by cyanide addition to produce the alpha-aminonitrile serine nitrile.", "reasoning": "Foden et al. identify serine nitrile as the correct upstream entry point to prebiotic cysteine chemistry, and glycolaldehyde is a well-established Strecker precursor to serine nitrile in the Sutherland/Powner framework (Foden et al., 2020; Patel et al., 2015). This is the productive route, in contrast to the failed direct Strecker route to cysteine."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Chemoselective N,O-diacetylation of serine nitrile", "inputs": ["mol_009", "mol_010"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)", "phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "room temperature", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "ferricyanide oxidant in aqueous solution", "aqueous": true, "other": "pH 7; 1 hour; chemoselective acyl transfer by thioacetic acid"}, "mechanism": "Thioacetic acid transfers acetyl groups to both the amino and hydroxyl functions of serine nitrile under mild aqueous conditions.", "reasoning": "This is the key activating step of the Powner biomimetic pathway: serine nitrile is converted to N,O-diacetylserine nitrile in 91% yield at pH 7 and room temperature using thioacetic acid and ferricyanide (Foden et al., 2020). Thioacetic acid acts as both acyl donor and sulfur source."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Beta-elimination to N-acetyl-dehydroalanine nitrile", "inputs": ["mol_011"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "room temperature", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "intrinsic alpha-nitrile activation", "aqueous": true, "other": "pH 8; 4 days; 85% conversion"}, "mechanism": "The alpha-nitrile activates near-neutral-pH beta-elimination from O-acetyl serine nitrile to the unusually stable dehydroalanine nitrile derivative.", "reasoning": "Foden et al. showed that N,O-diacetylserine nitrile eliminates at pH 8 and room temperature to N-acetyl-dehydroalanine nitrile in 85% conversion, whereas the corresponding amide does not. This nitrile-enabled elimination is the central breakthrough solving the cysteine problem (Foden et al., 2020)."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Alternative phosphoserine-like elimination route to dehydroalanine nitrile", "inputs": ["mol_011"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "333K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Mg2+ 40 mM with phosphate-rich setting", "aqueous": true, "other": "60C; 1 day; alternative route with 24% yield"}, "mechanism": "An alternative elimination manifold under Mg2+-assisted warm aqueous conditions also accesses the same dehydroalanine nitrile hub, though less efficiently.", "reasoning": "Foden et al. reported an alternative phosphoserine-inspired route giving N-acetyl-dehydroalanine nitrile under Mg2+ (40 mM) at 60C in 24% yield. It is a lower-yield but literature-supported convergent access to the same hub intermediate (Foden et al., 2020)."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Sulfide addition to N-acetyl-dehydroalanine nitrile", "inputs": ["mol_012", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "room temperature", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "aqueous sulfide addition", "aqueous": true, "other": "near-neutral pH; near-quantitative sulfur incorporation"}, "mechanism": "Hydrosulfide performs conjugate addition to the activated dehydroalanine nitrile, generating the cysteine thioamide derivative.", "reasoning": "Foden et al. showed that N-acetyl-dehydroalanine nitrile reacts with H2S in near-quantitative yield to give N-acetylcysteine thioamide under mild aqueous conditions. This is the decisive sulfur incorporation step (Foden et al., 2020)."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Thioacetic-acid addition to dehydroalanine nitrile leading to acetylated cysteine derivative", "inputs": ["mol_012", "mol_010"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)", "phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "room temperature", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "aqueous thioester-forming addition followed by hydrolytic workup", "aqueous": true, "other": "pH 7; ~12 hours for quantitative thioester formation; connected here to the acetylated cysteine pool"}, "mechanism": "Thioacetic acid adds across the activated alkene to form an acetylated cysteine precursor pool that can furnish N-acetylcysteine-related products.", "reasoning": "Foden et al. reported that N-acetyl-dehydroalanine nitrile reacts quantitatively with thioacetic acid at pH 7 to yield a cysteine thioester manifold; subsequent ammonolysis or thiolysis furnishes cysteine derivatives. This reaction is represented as converging into the N-acetylcysteine derivative pool for network connectivity while preserving the experimentally established sulfur-addition chemistry (Foden et al., 2020)."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "Hydrolysis/deprotection of N-acetylcysteine thioamide to N-acetylcysteine", "inputs": ["mol_013"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "298-333K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": true, "other": "mild aqueous hydrolysis in prebiotic pools"}, "mechanism": "Thioamide hydrolysis under mild aqueous conditions converts the sulfur-incorporated nitrile-derived intermediate into the stable acetylated amino acid pool.", "reasoning": "Foden et al. established sulfur addition products such as N-acetylcysteine thioamide and related acetylated cysteine derivatives as accessible endpoints of the biomimetic sequence. Their conversion to the N-acetylcysteine pool is a necessary connecting hydrolysis/deprotection step and is therefore included as a conservative downstream transformation consistent with the reported product manifold (Foden et al., 2020; explicitly connective but less directly quantified than the preceding steps)."}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "Deacetylation of N-acetylcysteine to cysteine", "inputs": ["mol_014"], "outputs": ["mol_015"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "298-333K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": true, "other": "mild hydrolytic deacylation in concentrated prebiotic pools or compartments"}, "mechanism": "Hydrolytic cleavage of the N-acetyl group liberates free cysteine from the protected cysteine reservoir.", "reasoning": "Free cysteine is expected to arise from deprotection/hydrolysis of the acety