nts UV photolysis of reduced CH4/C2H6/NH3/H2O/H2S mixtures rather than a simple two-component system; low yield"}, "mechanism": "H2S-sensitized UV radical chemistry in reduced gas-water systems generates low amounts of sulfur amino acids including cysteine/cystine.", "reasoning": "Khare & Sagan (1971) and Sagan & Khare (1971) directly detected cysteine/cystine from UV photolysis experiments using reduced mixtures containing hydrocarbons, NH3, H2O, and H2S, with H2S acting as a photosensitizer. This branch is retained as a low-yield classical route and is intentionally encoded as a broad atmospheric-mixture pathway rather than an invalid underspecified one-step conversion (Khare & Sagan, 1971; Sagan & Khare, 1971)."}, {"id": "rxn_016", "name": "Decarboxylation of cysteine to cysteamine", "inputs": ["mol_015"], "outputs": ["mol_016"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "320-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": true, "other": "thermal or geochemically assisted decarboxylation in prebiotic pools"}, "mechanism": "Loss of the carboxyl group converts cysteine into cysteamine, linking amino acid sulfur chemistry to coenzyme-like thiol chemistry.", "reasoning": "Cysteamine is the thiol moiety of coenzyme A and has long been considered a plausible prebiotic sulfur metabolite; the literature review explicitly highlights the cysteine-to-cysteamine connection in prebiotic networks (Miller & Schlesinger, 1993; Fairchild et al., 2024). This step is included as a downstream biochemical connection rather than as part of the core target-forming route."}], "pathways": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "name": "Canonical cyanosulfidic-to-biomimetic cysteine route", "description": "Dominant literature-supported route: HCN/H2S photoredox chemistry gives glycolaldehyde, which undergoes Strecker synthesis to serine nitrile and then the Foden biomimetic sequence to cysteine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "r